While I think this game is better than Escape The Backrooms, the performance of this game is TERRIBLE (Especially in VR)

My GPU is a 4080, my CPU is a 5700X, and my HMD is a Quest 3 (connected via SteamLinkVR on a wifi6 network). On the default resolution scale of SteamVR (150% in my case) the game will run at less than 1 FPS on low graphics with antialiasing, SSR, and Volumetric lights off. 

The maximum resolution the game runs at is 1784x1912, a single pixel higher and the game will run at 1 FPS instead of the 72 I have it set to target

The game uses insane amounts of VRAM, so if you are using an older card the game may perform even worse.

Alongside this, the most recent level added to the game WILL NOT LAUNCH IN VR.
The old VR lobby was incredibly disorientating since it locked your view, the new lobby is even worse since it locks your view AND puts you in third person without a theater screen. There are also some points in maps where you will be teleported if you are playing in VR.

The levels themselves are decent (puzzles, environment), but the AI is a little basic and doesn't really pose much of a threat.

I give the game a 5.5/10 overall (3.5/10 for VR), most of this is due to performance issues and bugs (like join in progress not working EVER)
I personally believe that the devs added the workshop feature as an excuse to stop adding new content to the game, so I do not believe any of the issues will ever be addressed.

I would not recommend buying the game as it is today, but if you just want a quick few hours of horror with the homies it's ok, nothing special.

This game is a horror classic at this point in time, but there are flaws. I personally, and take this with a grain of salt, do not like how difficult this game is just playing through the first two levels. Apparently this game has over 1,000 levels, and I could barely put a dent in that number. The main reason for this was that the monsters were too powerful and that the map was very large and hard to manage where to go. Even though that's the point, it was executed poorly in my vision. I'm going to leave it at that. The game has a lot of opportunity, and I really do believe that it is one of the greats in the horror genre, but I myself wouldn't classify this cherry at the top of my list. Go for it if you want a challenge, and go for it for the practically unlimited game play options and mechanics.

I consider myself a pretty big fan of any backrooms style games/lore/etc. Escape the backrooms spoiled me. 

This game has clunky AI, weird character models, strange movement and confusing puzzles that take away from the ambience of the backrooms. If you *really* like the backrooms, you MIGHT enjoy this game. 

But if you're looking to just jump on a game and face some mild challenges & have a good time for a bit, I don't think you're going to have a good time. 
My group and I spent half of our time being soft-locked out of a room because of a bunch of tiny goblins camping a doorway (albeit, I think they were from the Christmas event only, but still) and it immediately sucked the fun out of it and just made it a pain. Not worth the $ in my opinion.

There's no time to use the items before you die. You need to press I (inventory), click on item and then use item.

I had friends to play this game with. Anywho, Project MKUltra was an illegal human experimentation program designed and undertaken by the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency and intended to develop procedures and identify drugs that could be used during interrogations to weaken people and force confessions through brainwashing and psychological torture. It began in 1953 and was halted in 1973. MKUltra used numerous methods to manipulate its subjects' mental states and brain functions, such as the covert administration of high doses of psychoactive drugs and other chemicals without the subjects' consent, electroshocks, hypnosis, sensory deprivation, isolation, verbal and sexual abuse, and other forms of torture. MKUltra was preceded by Project ARTICHOKE. It was organized through the CIA's Office of Scientific Intelligence and coordinated with the United States Army Biological Warfare Laboratories. The program engaged in illegal activities, including the use of U.S. and Canadian citizens as unwitting test subjects.

i normally dont leave reviews for random games like this but this one was just so good. i never really knew about the backrooms before playing this but after i beat this game i was so interested in the actual lore and watched so many videos on it. the game is so much fun. it has co op which i recommend you do because it makes it 100x better. you essentially go through different stages of the backrooms and solve multiple puzzles all while running away and hiding from different entities that roam each level of the backrooms. you find lore hidden about in each stage and it creates more mystery and questions about the backrooms. what is this place? why did scientist come here? how did they come here? what was their goal? the game does a good job at creating this feeling of mystery and uneasiness about the environments. its a cheap game by price which makes it worth the time even more. go ahead and tell your friends about this game and play it together, youll have plenty of fun.

Every time I went to join another game through the "join game" option, my game would soft lock and i wouldn't be able to do anything until I actually force-quit the game which, mind you, I can't even do it through the standard steam menu vr button, I had to take the headset off and use task manager to do it. If I can't even access my steam menu through the button that is supposed to bring it up in a game where I have to recenter myself, that's already a red flag for me. But, despite that, I powered through. I got to an elevator portion in which I tried every combination under the sun, even looking around for any extra clues and whatnot and it wouldn't let me out of that one section. I'm getting a refund as soon as I figure out how. 
TL;DR 
-Can't join other multiplayer lobbies
-For some reason I can't access the steam menu normally through the button mapped for it(whether that is the dev's fault or a fault of the headset itself is beyond me, but this is the only game that had the issue, so take that for what you will)
-Elevator portion is either impossible to get past or it might just be a skill issue. 
-The in-game pause menu is a little annoying to keep still as it follows your head to some degree, making it easy to make a wrong selection.

If running around from monsters and having to do puzzles at the same time is your thing, this is your game. If not, skip playing it. The atmosphere is there but it doesn't last long, while you become immersed in searching the clues for puzzles.
One huge disadvantage is how OP the lockers are. You are essentially immune while entering it (mid animation) and even if  the barbed wire monster sees you enter it, he can't remove you out of it to insta-kill you or at least to continue the chase.
As a last thing, it's rather forgiving. You receive plenty of supplies to stay alive and monsters have a big spawn interval so you can figure out clues for the next puzzle.

But overall, as a personal opinion, compared to other games found on the market of multiplayer horror, it's not worth spending your time on in.

If the single-player option had a 'save' function of some sort, this game would be close to golden.

No save option = no thumbs up. 

Having a busy life precludes being held hostage by a game that chose such an omission intentionally.

Other than that, there have been only minor (but persistent) glitches so far, smooth controls, great graphics overall, and a solid take on the Backrooms genre. I'd rank it in the top five or six Backrooms games, and would rank it higher if not for the head-bob mechanic (nearly universally loathed, but someone out there always thinks it will add realism to their game. I don't get a headache when I walk down the street, and I shouldn't get one when my character does in a poor attempt to mimic greater realism) and the aforementioned lack of a fu*king save option.

Lastly, there's an awful lot going on for a Backrooms game. I'm avoiding entities, navigating a maze, collecting body parts, looking for VHS tapes, manipulating sculptures to open secret doors, looking for a key and looking for the door that it opens, assigning my collected body parts to the right bodies, looking for clock parts for another puzzle, finding anti-radiation protection and using a Geiger-counter to find more mysteries, and this is all just in the first level...and there may be more as I haven't completed all of this due to the lack of a save function and having to start over each time!

an objectively wrong interpretation of the backrooms. This game is basically a cheap knock off horror game that is flawed in so many areas. 

problems:

Lighting. Its way too dark everywhere from what a normal version of the backrooms would be. It has that mystical black fog effect, so when you've got a flash light shining it really only shows you about twenty feet before dissipating into darkness. I'm guessing this was done to make it more spooky, fear of the dark and what not. But the specific horror the backrooms entails is not the claustrophobia, its the idea of huge spaces that are vastly empty and familiar. In other words, if the lighting was better and allowed you to see much further, it would add to that visual and psychological spook element the backrooms is known for.

Stamina: bad. So there are three movements. There's either walk at a tip toe pace, or there's crouch walk at an even slower tip toe pace, and then there's sprint which is drained quite fast. Essentially, you're best bet to not get murdered by an entity is to walk at a snails pace, and then only sprint once its spotted you and you have to run away. Basically to play smart you have to play painfully slow and boring. Ultimately, you're going to sprint a little bit to get places, which means that at some point you're going to be running from a monster, run out of sprint, and then you are simply forced to walk at a snails pace while an entity is whacking you. Simply put it is just not the way to do it. It feels absolutely wrong and wonky to imagine tip toeing away from a monster that's wacking your ass. the non sprint speed should be a little faster, fast enough to be reasonable. If necessary to add difficulty back, lower the sprint speed slightly but increase the walking speed. This would balance everything out and play with so much better flow, not having to tip toe all the time at a snails pace.  

Entities: Neutral. Not factoring in the whole running out of sprint and having to tip toe away from an entity, the entities actually feel quite respectable. They look scary enough and behave in a way that I would say seems appropriate for the quality of this game. My only complaint is ive seen entities walk straight through doors which seems cheap. Overall I'd say entities are a neutral element in the game, they aren't excellent and they aren't poorly done either. SPOILER ALERT- there is one segment in the pool rooms where you have to navigate past a BUNCH of these arm spaghetti human meat ball looking things, and there's like a dozen if not more of them in one pool. You have to go around them and if you go to close they eat you. I think theres simply too many of them for it to be considered fair. END SPOILER.

Gameplay: Bad. It's pretty much entirely puzzle oriented. And its way too many puzzles and each one is unnecessarily difficult. Expect to look up multiple guides per level. For example on the second level i believe, you have to solve like four puzzles to progress which feels absolutely off. (there's two lock boxes that require inputting a simple code... why two lock boxes? theres already two other puzzles so just have one lock box, its already more than enough. Put both items in the same box). And they aren't easy either. They involve finding over half a dozen parts that are randomly scattered in lockers, so loot EVERYTHING. If anything this game becomes more of an intellectual puzzle game than a horror or backrooms game. It is just so off. Every level I had to look up multiple guides maybe except the parking lot, since that one doesn't really have puzzles. I'm assuming most of the backrooms audience members are kids, and I honestly cant imagine anyone below the age of 14 being a serious contender for being able to beat this game. I think its like 3 or 5 bucks, well personally I would pay another 5 bucks to have not played it and gotten my time back. It's difficult where it shouldn't be difficult and its easy where it shouldn't be easy. Probably the least fun game ive played in years.

final complaint. I beat the game, got through what was the old ending and even got to a game completion screen and woke up. I knew there was a sewers level so i was confused. I went to the menu to see if it had been unlocked since i  "beat" the game allegedly. Nope. Sewers is still locked for me, despite progressing through everything prior to it. Thanks. so basically i put in all the effort to progress through the first 3 or 4 levels, just so i can be denied accessing another 2 levels that i presumably paid for. Theres some youtube guides on the sewer levels but they dont mention it having any quirks or weird pre requisites to unlock. im either guessing something was changed in an update or maybe it requires another purchase as some kind of DLC, either way some kind of notification or identification as to whats going on would be helpful, preferably in the menu where it can say whats going on, whether it needs an extra dlc purchase or what. Cant in good faith recommend this game to a single person.

Title: A Surreal Journey Into the Unknown - Inside the Backrooms Review

Rating: ★★★★☆

Inside the Backrooms is a captivating exploration into the enigmatic and bizarre realm of the unknown. This indie game, developed by a small team with a passion for the surreal, offers a unique and unsettling experience that will leave you questioning reality.

The game's premise is simple yet intriguing: you find yourself trapped inside a series of interconnected, dimly lit rooms that seem to stretch on endlessly. The minimalist graphics and atmospheric sound design work in harmony to create an eerie ambiance that keeps you on edge throughout the journey. The sense of isolation and claustrophobia is palpable, adding to the overall sense of unease.

One of the standout features of Inside the Backrooms is its procedurally generated levels, ensuring that no two playthroughs are the same. This unpredictability contributes to the game's replay value, as you never know what twisted surprises await you around each corner. The developers have successfully captured the essence of internet urban legends and creepy pasta, bringing them to life in a way that's both unsettling and fascinating.

The lack of a clear narrative may be a drawback for some players seeking a more structured storyline, but for those who enjoy a more abstract and interpretive experience, Inside the Backrooms offers a canvas for the imagination. The game encourages players to piece together their own narrative from the fragments scattered throughout the unsettling environments.

However, the game isn't without its flaws. Some may find the controls a bit clunky, especially when navigating tight spaces or trying to avoid lurking threats. Additionally, the randomness of the procedural generation can occasionally lead to frustrating dead ends or situations where progression feels unfairly hindered.

In conclusion, Inside the Backrooms is a commendable indie title that successfully taps into the psychological horror genre. It may not be for everyone, but if you're a fan of atmospheric experiences that leave you with a lingering sense of disquiet, this game is well worth a try. Just be prepared to question your sanity as you navigate the haunting corridors of the backrooms

[b]¿En conclusión?[/b] Es como Escape the Backrooms, pero sin sus pros y acrecentando sus contras.

On the other side, there are some good jump scares and really good level design that makes the game really fun to play with a friend. The game is also replayable, as most of the combinations and clues are slightly different each playthrough. Recommend.

It was like wandering through a maze of endless beige hallways, where each flickering light bulb revealed a lurking terror. The atmosphere was suffocating, as if the stale air whispered secrets from the forgotten corners. I found myself questioning reality, trapped between the mundane and the macabre. The developers captured the essence of the Backrooms, immersing me in a world where every wrong turn could lead to a spine-chilling encounter. It was like being lost in a surreal nightmare, where the walls watched me with an eerie gaze.

So, my adventurous friends, if you dare to venture into the abyss of the Backrooms, be prepared for a bone-chilling experience that will make your heart race and your mind unravel. This game will leave you trembling, like a leaf caught in an eternal "wah wah wee wah" dance. Embrace the fear, and may your journey through the Backrooms be both terrifying and exhilarating.

I am writing this review to discuss the topic of what game to buy, Inside the Backrooms, or Escape the Backrooms. They are both Backrooms themed escape room games but there are pros and cons to both. This review is coming from someone who has played both games with a friend (no singleplayer experience). If you are looking for a fun backrooms themed escape room game to play with a friend, Inside the backrooms is the game you should buy. Escape the backrooms seems to follow more of the lore of the backrooms while Inside the backrooms seems like an escape room game that is Backrooms themed. In Inside the backrooms each level is carefully crafted with puzzels that interlock with eachother. Escape the backrooms just seems to have an exit somewhere and plop you into a new area. Escape the backrooms has many more levels compared to inside the backrooms, but they can be short (15min). Inside the backrooms has many puzzels to each level and can keep you inside one level for sometimes 2 hours (there are also multiple endings). Inside the backrooms does not have a sanity meter like Escape the backrooms but if anything I think that makes the game better even though it is not as realistic to the actual lore. The walkie talkie situation in Inside the backrooms is a bit annoying so I would recommend using a third-party voice chat app. Overall I think Inside is the better game because it is more catered to the experience of the player (there are emotes) while Escape the backrooms is more trying to imitate the lore of the backrooms (no emotes), but if you have money to spare def buy both. Oh and playing with friends makes both games a blast to play.

[h1]The Gameplay: [/h1]
Play yet another backrooms games with puzzles and stuff to do with friends. The puzzles in this one are often laden with too much pressure that honestly just makes it no longer fun. To that end, while you have a generous amount of health to be able to take hits, the amount of entities that you can encounter is honestly too much and makes the game less scary and more annoying than anything. The tension almost never gets to build up.

[h1]The Story:[/h1]
You are John Backstreet Boy and you get sucked into the backrooms by a fucking .jpg, It honestly awful that there is some weird ass entity at all there, it just looks dumb. It would be better if you just stumbled in there or if that scene were done with proper creepy tension instead of whatever that was.

[h1]The Visuals:[/h1]
This is one of the best looking backrooms multiplayer games. Especially in regards to the characters and the way they look wearing the hunchback banana pajama outfit. The animations are still quite jank especially the way your character leans forward with the posture of a drinking bird in stasis.

[h1]The Sound:[/h1]
The voice acting in this game is dog water. It's a level of bad where I feel anyone can do a better job than what was done. I'd offer to do the lines for free if it meant I did not have to hear that dumpster fire of a performance. The ambiance and sfx for the entities is one of the pillars to this game's sound work. Too bad the entitles get spammed so much that the sounds they make actually becomes obnoxious.


[h1]The Experience:[/h1]
After coming off the heals of Escape the Backrooms, I expected that this would be a much more premium experience. While enjoyable, it certainly was not. It scratches an  itch, but it also just feels like a chore. Here do a puzzle while I swarm you with enemies you have to run from every 2 seconds. It had a cool/scare factor for the first 5 minutes, then it just became just an annoyance. The party room puzzles were notably, neat in concept but mostly just a frustrating mess. The writing was also bad, and too confidently placed in the game for it to not be issue. Overall the experience was mid, and you would be better off playing a different backrooms game for now. Hopefully development does not stop on this game so I can change my overall recommendation.

Gonna be completely honest in this review. At first when I got this game to enjoy with some friends we got so demotivated because the features of the game just didn't suit us. Therefore, the game as it is NOW is actually very nice. The devs have made some major changes to the game in a short amount of time. We decided to give it a new go and it is now exactly what we wanted the first time we played it. Sure, there are scarier games out there. BUT, this game is a lot of fun with friends and it gives a good scare. The price is also good and just overall, I have nothing really bad to say about the game anymore. I found it well balanced. Edit: As of 2/24/2023, 2nd Edit 10/3/2023
Alright I'll break it down for ya with this game, it's not bad, some good horror aspects and everything I'll give it that, with all the updates and everything that have come out and the areas as well as the recent inclusion of workshop support, this game is I think worth it, mainly with friends is where the game shines, It's more puzzle oriented in aspects compared too the horror.

For actual progression things are simpler than they used to be, spawn locations for items and other such things are not terrible, and can be found with just a bit of looking.

It has quite a few backrooms levels that, well are based on the backrooms yes, there's not any random generation for the levels themselves just the items so repeated runs will have that issue.

In terms of content there's a lot of levels here, but for still a main issue, the sewer is not very fun, it has been reworked since my original review, now it is MOST CERTAINLY easier to manage, the entire level isn't water, less rats and more interconnected paths so it won't take you 10 years to run back and forth, however the level is still rather long, with far far too many puzzles for me to comfortably enjoy.

It's worth it for the price, and a not too bad horror game with friedns if you can give it a go.

My first backrooms game I've played, it's pretty good for a horror game, especially with friends.

However it can be very tedious if you're not sure what to do, as you need to look for items that can be hard to spot. Puzzles are also randomized, meaning you can't watch a video or look up the guide to get all the immediate answers you need. Example, if you need to enter a password for something, it will always be different each time you play.

Also, entities (or just one) spawn randomly, which can be a pain if you're trying to do something and they keep chasing you causing you to run or hide constantly.

Despite the possible time consuming gameplay, I still enjoyed almost every second of it. 

For $7 it's worth it's price imo with updates still rolling out. Overall, 7.5/10.

This pathetic debacle of a game is the most piss poor take on the backrooms that I've ever had the displeasure of running on my computer. The sewer and grassroom areas I thought would be a fresh new take on the game since there was an update and I'd attempted to play it twice with my friends already and despised the way I felt afterwards. I was hopeful and left with extreme contempt. 

The puzzles are grueling and exhausting to play through, the steps to complete each chapter were tedious and unforgiving, and after the first 20 minutes of playing it feels like you've been playing for a hour. Playing the game made me wonder if the developers played it themselves before subjecting people to this reprehensible product. The stamina system is flawed and requires entirely too much time to refill if you're being chased by an enemy. It takes less time to cook a hot pocket in the microwave. Upon dying you need to find a door to respawn but the sound indicators such as the heartbeat and angelic harmony bug out and don't occur. Also the trail of light is very obscure and is seldom an accurate path to follow to reach your door. Often times I would respawn and be insta-killed because the enemy that killed me was still stomping around on my body to revel at what they'd accomplished (though it didn't take very much). 

Save your time and money. You'd be doing yourself a service by staying as far away from this game as possible. It's not interesting, captivating, or rewarding.
The developers have worked hard to improve what was originally an incredibly frustrating experience. It's not perfect, though. Your progress is tied to your steam achievements instead of a save file.

If you're looking to play a scary backrooms co-op horror, then this is your game. There is plenty of content with a lot of fun puzzles and challenges. The multiplayer system is really well executed (where if you die you lose a life and can respawn and continue to play with friends). There is a in-game reward system for completing the tougher achievements this game has to offer making the grind significantly more entertaining. You can customise your characters and there are holiday events. The only issue with this game is that it is not perfectly lore accurate (but that is an INCREDIBLY MINOR COMPLAINT).

this game contains the most tedious unenjoyable puzzles that lead to a payoff that does not feel rewarding at all. near the end, the only sense of pleasure i got once i complete a level is the knowledge that it is finally over. i walk at the pace of a lethargic handicapped american citizen, and i have the stamina bar to match. aesthetically and atmospherically the first three levels are great, with unique environments that keep the game refreshing. once you reach the sewers, the game loses that atmosphere and you're met with enemies placed and paths crafted in the most inconvenient ways in order to pad out the game's playtime. the enemies aren't scary in the slightest, and are moreso just an inconvenience designed to stall out your objectives as much as possible. mechanically, the game tries in many ways but fails in even more. whenever a player dies, they drop all items on the ground and must pick them up once they respawn. this becomes very tedious in the long run, especially if a player forgets to pick up their items. overall the concept of the game is good, but every one of those concepts is executed in a way that feels unpolished and designed to drag out the experience as much as possible which leads to a boring experience. the game also has a few technical problems, with the AI being horrible and VR being nearly unplayable due to many features not  being updated for VR. if you're looking for a good backrooms experience, there are many games that pull it off better in every way.

Venturing into the enigmatic and terrifying world of Inside the Backrooms is a haunting experience that will forever be etched into the depths of my memory. From the very first step, this first-person horror game plunged me into a realm of unrelenting fear, where the boundary between reality and nightmare is chillingly blurred.

Inside the Backrooms delivers a masterclass in suspense and horror, immersing players into a grim and unsettling environment where escape becomes a desperate struggle for survival. The mere premise of navigating through a labyrinthine expanse of backrooms is enough to send shivers down one's spine, and the game executes this concept with an eerie finesse that is both captivating and terrifying.

The absence of detailed information about the game only serves to heighten the atmosphere of mystery and dread. As I cautiously tread through dimly lit corridors and long-forgotten passages, the unsettling silence is punctuated only by the echoes of my own footsteps. Every turn and every shadow seems to harbor an unknown horror, leaving me perpetually on edge, my heart pounding in anticipation of what nightmarish creature or malevolent force might lurk just beyond my field of vision.

The monsters that inhabit the Backrooms are nothing short of nightmares personified. Each encounter is a heart-pounding race against terror, as I scramble to escape the clutches of these monstrous entities that seem to exist solely to induce fear. The sense of vulnerability is palpable, and every fleeting glimpse of these abominations is enough to send a chilling shiver down my spine.

The game's ability to manipulate atmosphere and tension is a testament to its design prowess. The interplay of light and shadow, the haunting soundscapes, and the oppressive sense of isolation all contribute to an experience that is deeply immersive and utterly spine-chilling. Every creaking floorboard, every distant whisper, serves to remind me that I am never truly alone in this forsaken place.

As I navigate the treacherous terrain of Inside the Backrooms, the quest for escape takes on a profound psychological dimension. The constant threat of danger and the palpable feeling of dread make each decision a life-or-death gamble. Every door opened, every step taken, is fraught with the anticipation of what horrors might be unveiled, and the relentless tension never loosens its grip.

Inside the Backrooms is not merely a game; it's an exploration of fear's darkest recesses, a plunge into the abyss of the unknown, and an adrenaline-fueled journey into the heart of horror. Its ability to immerse players in an atmosphere of chilling uncertainty, coupled with its relentless pursuit of terror, sets it apart as a masterpiece in the realm of first-person horror experiences. If you're seeking an unforgettably harrowing adventure that will test your courage and keep you on the edge of your seat, then brace yourself for the spine-tingling descent into the nightmarish depths of Inside the Backrooms.

I had an overall negative experience of this game, starting from the later half of level 2 and continuing through to the end. This is not to say that the game is bad however, the first level was very well made, the objectives of it were made clear and it was, overall, a very good level. Below you will find my dislikes. 

My gripes begin with the transition of the parking lot into the office, the puzzles started to become convoluted and (at least to me and my friend) seemingly not thought out, notes began to be unreliable as they read very strangely or provided little to no actual hint on what to do, the levels begin to become quite large (and at this point far more difficult), enemy spawns in these levels worked well, to a degree but could be tweaked slightly.

The partygoer section was truly terrible you are given vague hints on what to do "find your gift" , you would assume that this meant there would be one for each player, there is not. Another reason why i claim this top be terrible is the time limit, when wandering through the maze it was incredibly hard to know where to go, finally the partygoer did not use its own rules (this is prevalent in the part where you need to blow out candles). After this the game only gets worse. 

The sewer level. My god. what an abhorrent level. It was far too large for its own good, it was incredibly difficult to know where I was going, the puzzles were terrible, there were no hints to tell us what we needed to do or where we needed to go, for example, the medallions. You need three medallions in order to get a cog, a friend and I spent at least an hour wandering round just trying to find the final medallion all while avoiding as many enemies as possible (which was an incredibly difficult task considering how many hand dudes were wandering about). When we actually find the way to get it we felt it was incredibly stupid as there was no way we could've seen the door in the wall unless we were actually looking for it.

The terror hotel was all in all, a decent level. it was still convoluted and we found that it was a very very poor experience, it would be better to put the door number on the door instead of above it. The steam generator puzzle was aggravating as it had no actual effect on the moths. the gem puzzle was pretty silly, considering that there is no apparent way to pick up the fossils, (the only reason that we were able to do it was because i accidentally clicked on the fossil) due to the glass covering the fossil it would make more sense that you would need to break the glass, but no, you just need to reach through the glass instead. It would make more sense to remove the glass from the puzzle all together as it adds nothing to it. The puzzles were vague and didn't make a lot of sense.

Overall:
The first level is the undeniably the best,
The puzzles start of well but get progressively worse
The increase of map size, puzzles and entity amount per level do not equate to a good experience
The player models and enemy models were well made.

I do not think that it was worthwhile to purchase, it did however provide my friend and I a good experience for an hour or two. I only hope that you find it to be far better than I did.

first the positives, the beginning of the game was most enjoyable, the puzzles were layed out, easy to figure out and the map was easy to traverse, it was very understanding in what you needed to do where, with parts just layed out in front of you so you could figure out without trouble what to do, the enemies were iconic and well designed with game mechanics that anyone can get behind.

now the negatives, the second half of the game (mainly the rat sewer level and also the "terror" hotel) were poorly designed, the sewer level was FARRRRRR to large with endless amounts of slow and tedious back tracking, with horrible key item placements in ridiculous random spots guarded by enemies with too big a hit box with horrible pathing in too cramped a space. actually figuring out what to do can take hours, but then actually doing the task can take twice as long, over half the play time was just for figuring out where only a select amount of the key item in the sewer were. it was near impossible to figure out everything wit the copious amounts of enemies with horrible pathing and conflicting game mechanics (having to sneak for the rat and hands, then having to run from the ugo dog). the "terror" hotel was a good map size BUT there were far too many enemies that were more annoying then anything in a really cramped space where it was really easy to run and get stuck on anything and everything. the ending moth section was weird and buggy and the game didnt make sense on how the steam would actually effect the moths and they just continued to attack me.

in conclusion, the first half is worth the play, the second is a massive steaming pile of dogshit and shouldnt be played until it is reworked or fixed to have A. a smaller more understandable sewer level with properly detailed instructions on where small key items are B. the moths are fixed to actually be effected by the steam at the end of the hotel C. the pathing for the sewer enemies are fixed (they stick to and phase through walls and corners and can attack you through certain walls because of this) D. all objectives are fully understandable (not said exactly what to do but less cryptic and more of a slight guidance of a certain area you do need to be in) E. have objects have key commands on them so then you know how to properly interact with them because it can be confusing when certain turn by pulling left or right and then others are to be turnt with a circle motion or clicked and dragged, when they can just be clicked

Game was fun to play with others, while not scary it is still easy to get jumped and scare yourself and your friends with constant screaming when getting chased down.

but there are very big problems with the game as of currently
-monsters hard camp, very annoying when your basically stuck in a locker for 10 minutes at a time
-random stuff like gas out of the walls or vents isnt explained so its just kinda happening around you without reason
-big one is that there is no way to choose between levels, we finished the first level after 2 hours and wanted to continue later but had to try and speedrun to the office instead after replaying the entire first thing when we came back
-there are no settings to distinct how many lives you have in game, in the description of the game it says you have 3 so you expect that but instead have 10 for each person right now
-again description of the game is wrong, it says there are 4 levels but those aren't out currently or finished so it feels like a scam (hopefully it will be updated in the future but frankly a lot of the description is wrong)
- also items are shared between players, 1 screwdriver and hammer and motion detector to share between potentially 3 people. and during the pool part that is very hard to go through behind one person without everyone dying right at the end of the second level

all in all this was still fun and cool puzzles for the first time but still just frustrating and a lot of wasted time while being repeat killed at times

EDIT:Made that review about a year ago and since then the game has added multiple new levels and features that Im happy to say are great, i played this with a full party of friends each time and am doing this edit now as of august 1st 2023, I personally love the game, there is some things that honestly just didnt like and was a group consensus on being annoying but the game is being constantly updated and even grievances like before the safe being impossible to use half the time was fixed very shortly. 

For annoyances: -the party room maze, super annoying for most of us and the only way it was not infuriating was cause we were on easy mode with infinite lives, the game takes like a half hour if you're not afraid to die just for that one part and i cannot imagine doing that without the motion tracker or a finite amount of lives 
-the AI still is campy in the earlier levels, i understand its kinda what makes it scary but it just adds unnecessary time to the game cause you're waiting to get out of the locker for a lot of the beginning levels
-If you try and play with someone who hasnt hit a certain checkpoint then they just cant play with you, feels like its silly its not an option not to spawn them in with the same items as everybody else as thats what it does for anybody whose hit that point already, for anybody that hasnt and wants to play with their friends then you just gotta give up or go through the whole game from where there last checkpoint is 
-Ingame vc just sucks so use discord
-The sewer level in general just too big for no reason, the water making you slower and the fact that the place is huge is just a headache, we spent 3 hours on that level and half of its because the place is just too damn big for the amount of rooms it has 

Overall if you want a game to just play at 3 AM with a group of friends that are willing to goof around with you then despite all of this I still found this fun to play and would recommend it as  a experience for people to go through, the developer is still working on this and I do hope it keeps improving and providing more levels as I do find the puzzles to be fun when theyre not being wonky before patches

Inside The Backrooms takes you on a thrilling journey through the eerie layers of the Backrooms. It's a short yet satisfying horror game that captures the essence of the creepypasta lore. But there are a few things we wish we knew before delving into this spine-chilling adventure.

Stamina is a crucial factor, and running around recklessly will quickly drain it, leaving you vulnerable. Respawning is possible, but the door's location changes each time, so don't waste time searching for the same spot. Losing your flashlight means navigating in the dark or finding a replacement, as items don't respawn. 

Puzzles are randomly generated, adding replayability and keeping you on your toes.  Entities in the game may not follow the exact rules from the lore, so don't rely solely on your prior knowledge. The game's order of levels also deviates from the canon, offering a fresh experience. Beware of the birthday party section, as it presents the toughest challenge in the game by far. 

Lastly, while the ending may not be as satisfying as the rest of the game, it's still a worthwhile journey.

Inside The Backrooms is a game that creates tension and offers spooky thrills, but be aware the game as of this review is prone to crashes and glitches. While not present on my end, it was apparent and fairly noticable for a few of my friends. But for $7, I cant really complain.

I love Inside the Backrooms, it's fun and pretty atmospheric when you're relatively new to the game. The puzzles are extremely fun to go through and figure out (for the most part, there are a few that should be re-examined). I have but only a few complaints. Firstly the monsters. I feel as though some of the monsters (Entity #3 and partygoer) are kinda lame and hard to counter. 
To go in more depth; Entity 3 (creepy face) feels like it has little to no counter. It can spawn on your face and have a chance to kill you even though you didn't do anything. Also doesn't go away even if it has killed someone. As for partygoer, I have a huge problem with both the fun room and the creature. The creature in the first section is the worst part due to the fact that it will freeze you in the claustrophobia-inducing maze. It makes it feel crappy, even if you're about to die anyway. I feel as though the whole level needs a complete revamp on how it works. Or make it optional. 
Ignoring all of this; I would still absolutely recommend this to anyone who has an interest in backrooms related stuff or horror puzzle games in general.

Update after some new content got added:
I had high hopes, and we really gave it a chance, but the new content is absolutely terrible and just tedious for the sake of it. We reached the new sewer level, which is purposefully designed to be a maze that you have to run back and forth across dozens of times. There is no redeemable fun quality to the game, it's not worth your money.

Do not let my playtime fool you. I negatively reviewed it before and we gave it another chance for the new endings and gave up.

This game is objectively bad. It is a travesty of game design. The enemies are unavoidable, the puzzles are boring, and the sewer level in particular is a tedious chore. Walk across the map slowly through sludge, find out you need something from the opposite corner, go back and forth, rinse and repeat. After two hours of trudging back and forth, we realised we still hadn't encountered at least three puzzles referenced in some notes and we decided we'd sooner become sanitation workers in real life because at least it would be rewarding.

The first level will see you cornered by all three enemies at once, you hide in a locker for a while, go to leave the room and they chase you back to the locker. There is no strategy, just luck and patience, of which mine is wearing thin.

How this game has ANY positive reviews is genuinely unfathomable.

No one wants to enter the same level again after leaving the game half-way through. Finally, there is a frustrating bug/glitch where if you are playing with other players, and one person enters the exit door at the final level and triggers the final story. Then, everybody who isn't finished yet will be automatically kicked out of the game. I would definitely recommend the game but be prepared to spend a couple hours completing the level you are on, if you don't want to restart on the same level the next time you play.

I would like to provide some feedback on this game based on my experience and the opinions of my friends:

1. Optimization Issues: The game suffers from poor optimization, causing frequent stutters even on hardware that meets the recommended requirements.

2. Graphics: The graphics in the game are subpar and fail to create an immersive experience.

3. Jump Scares: The game's attempts at jump scares are lackluster and fail to deliver the intended thrill.

4. AI: The AI in the game is disappointing, as it can be easily manipulated by breaking line of sight.

5. Puzzles: The puzzles in the game are not necessarily difficult, but rather tedious and lack coherence.

6. Voice Chat (VC) Issues: The voice chat feature in the game does not work properly.

7. Lack of Save Points: Surprisingly, the game lacks save points, which is a significant drawback. In our case, after spending an hour in the first level and dying repeatedly, we discovered that the game did not save our progress. This frustration prompted us to look up a walkthrough, only to realize that we were not even halfway through. This lack of save points was the final straw that led us to abandon the game.

If you're looking for a better Backrooms game experience, I highly recommend playing "Escape The Backrooms" instead. It offers a more satisfying and enjoyable gameplay experience.

I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 2021 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.
It's fun, it's hard, it's recommended.

[b]TL;DR[/b]: Inside the Backrooms is a co-op horror game where you solve escape room-style puzzles while being chased by entities from the The Backrooms mythos; while the concept itself is intriguing, the actual gameplay is tedious and frustrating.

[b]Gameplay[/b]:
The main gameplay loop revolves around solving escape room-style puzzles to progress through each level, with the added challenge of hostile entities from The Backrooms mythos lurking around every corner. While the concept sounds intriguing on paper, the gameplay becomes increasingly tedious the longer you play. The main problem is that the entities are simply way too oppressive, without there being any effective means of fending them off. While the game implies that each entity is attracted only to a specific action such as lights or radio communication, the only truly consistent way of avoiding an entity is by hiding in lockers. This is a huge problem as entities can sometimes camp an area you need to go to progress, and you are left simply hiding for prolonged periods waiting for it to leave. As a result, the gameplay experience very quickly devolves from horror to boredom or frustration.

[b]Level 1: Lobby[/b]
Moving on to the individual levels, the first level of the game is a reference to the iconic Backrooms Level 0, also known as "The Lobby". The entities in this level are Entity #3 Smiler, Entity #8 Hound, and the unknown entity from Kane Pixels' Backrooms video series. This level consists of multiple escape room-style puzzles, where each room have clues for a puzzle in a different room, which then unlocks a different puzzle in another room, until you finally unlock the exit. While these puzzles are initially interesting, the presence of three entities in a single level often results in extended periods of hiding and waiting. Very often, multiple entities appear at the same time, blocking both our path forwards and our retreat backwards. This results in us being unable to do anything but sit in place until the entities disappear. And while navigation in this level is supposed to be confusing by design with every turn and corner looking identical, the combination with the three entities have the effect of making the level feel unnecessarily prolonged and dragged out.

[b]Level 2: Parking[/b]
The second level of the game, Parking, most closely resembles The Backrooms Level 1, also known as the "Habitable Zone".  For some reason, this level was extremely short with the puzzles all being relatively straightforward, and the only entity on this level is Entity #10 Skin-Stealer. Nevertheless, this level does provide a refreshing change of pace, as rather than simply hiding from the entity, you get an opportunity to instead "fight back" against it by [spoiler]locking it out of the room[/spoiler].

[b]Level 3: Office[/b]
The third level, Office, combines elements from various levels in The Backrooms mythos. You start off in what looks like The Backrooms Level 5, also known as "Abandoned Office".  The gameplay of this level is very similar to the first level of the game, where you need to go around the level solving escape room-style puzzles. One upside of this level was that each room looked distinctly different from each other, making navigation somewhat more bearable. Unfortunately, the Entity #10 Skin-Stealers on this level is somehow an even more overwhelming presence than the three entities in the first level combined.

Afterwards, you enter a small room which contains a few objects taken from The Backrooms "Level Fun", albeit the surrounding environment is still that of an office. Here you will be challenged to a series of life and death minigames by the Partygoers. While the first minigame was rather pleasant, it very quickly devolves into just solving mazes in a given amount of time. Unfortunately, the game fails at the horror element in this section, as the short timer results in repeated deaths that becomes progressively less scary each time you respawn. While the mazes in and of itself are decently challenging without being completely disorienting, the repeated deaths very quickly sours the experience.

Next, we enter into a room containing just a huge swimming pool, with Entity #5 Clump lurking beneath the waters. If anything, I think this was actually the most scary part of the game since you were unable to physically see the entities, and the only way to avoid them was by [spoiler]detecting their location using a proximity sensor[/spoiler]. You could actually do this part without dying, which ironically made it more tense, especially when you see your friends in front of you get dragged underwater. However, there is one major design issue with this section. When you reach the end of the pool, the only way to proceed further is via [spoiler]a red keycard[/spoiler]. Yet, there is no indication of such a requirement prior to going through the pool. Should this happen, it means that you're forced to backtrack through the entity infested pool, with it feeling more frustrating than scary the second time around.

Finally, you once again enter into a section that resembles The Backrooms Level 0: "The Lobby". Except this time, it is even more of a maze than the first level of the game. In this section, you need to [spoiler]find the correct door while avoiding the fake ones[/spoiler]. The problem however, is that we didn't realize that if you [spoiler]enter a wrong door[/spoiler], an Entity #8 Hound is permanently unleashed into the maze. As there is no way to reset a level without starting from scratch, this mechanic feels unnecessarily punishing, because it means the more mistakes you make the harder the level gets. This makes the experience very frustrating, as you are constantly reminded of and regretting your mistake, while knowing that you wouldn't have had to deal with the entities if you did it correctly the first time.

[b]Level 4 and Level 5[/b]
For some reason, these 2 levels remain locked even after completing the previous level. It turns out that in order to unlock them, you must [spoiler]replay Level 3: Office and backtrack into Level 2: Parking while having the red keycard on you[/spoiler]. This is an extremely unsatisfying design choice, as the game is basically punishing us for finishing the game by keeping levels locked away from us, and forcing us to replay levels we've already beaten. At this point, I have not completed these levels, and should I end up playing them at a later date, it would only be due to my friends dragging me to play with them.

[b]Technical[/b]:
Aside from gameplay and design issue, the game also suffers from a few technical issues. Considering that this game seems primarily designed for co-op play, it is inexcusable that players are unable to rejoin a session after disconnecting. Not everyone has consistent and stable internet connections, so the possibility of disconnects is absolutely something that the game should have prepared for, especially given that a single level can take at least an hour to complete. Currently, should a player disconnect, the only way to get them back is to restart the entire level from scratch. This not only disrupts the flow of gameplay, but it is also a highly discouraging and frustrating experience.

Additionally, players with higher ping lags when attempting to use the in-game voice chat. While we were able to resolve this issue by communicating via Discord, it does detract from the immersion that the game was going for.

[b]Conclusion[/b]:
In conclusion, Inside the Backrooms presents an interesting concept, but numerous frustrating mechanics hinder the overall experience. While the game's puzzles and atmosphere initially captivate, it fails to strike the right balance between challenge and enjoyment. This serves as a reminder that less can be more, and that the absence of certain elements often evokes greater horror than their actual presence.

[b]Rating[/b]: 5.0 / 10.0

Now when I say broken, I don't just mean simple bugs with the gameplay, no.

I Bought this game around the time it came out and recently visited in during the Hotel And Sewer Updates and Found that this game is heading in a great direction and I'd love to see more out of it. It has a pretty good shock factor for the most part and has really good jump scares for the most part. This may look like a lazy backrooms game at first but I would definitely say that this has to be one of the best if not the best backroom game out of all of the replicas being made so far. The Models are actually pretty good as the enemies in the sewers and the hotel actually look very well and the Dead Rats have very good movement and animations. The Bad animations I don't really mind because it is a small company and they make updates where they can and the game is still enjoyable.
[Pros & Cons]
Pros

-Cheap Price
-Good Puzzles and Pretty Good Game play
-Good Scares
-Very Optimal Settings And Very Little Bugs
-Great Fun With Friends 
Cons
========
-Cheap Animations
-Repetitive Sound Effects

My group of friends usually play overwatch, but we eagerly wanted some other coop games that we can have fun and get scared (me) and not be mad at random teammates. And since this was cheap and early access, also watched some youtube videos of earlier levels and one of my friends got the game, we decided to try it!
The levels were big, with numerous puzzles that are connected to each other, a monster or two that dominates each level that we try to avoid. It's scary and I'm a scary cat, but I'm super excited to play this with my friends as they carry me and I focus on the puzzle solving XD. I like that vibe and types of puzzles in it, it's bad for someone who can't remember the map, but I can follow my friends so that's ok.
The one only complain rn is when we left the game midway (during sewers level) and went to eat dinner, the game froze for one of us, so we had to restart the whole level, but it wasn't too hard to catch up on the progress so wasn't too bad. Not sure if it's a steam issue or game but that's the only occurance so far. :)

It's kinda funny to say that the birthday room was one of the scariest experience but somehow I loved it even though it's scary and the idea is soo new and vibrant. I actually tough up and run around the corners to find the boxes since instead of hiding, it's better to find the boxes and pass each level.
There are some glitches like the rats try to chase a friend in the sewer and a group of them got stuck in the corner, which we happily enjoyed so we can run around to find clues when we get stuck XDD so we don't mind if you don't fix that haha.
I was also surprised that the birthday room level had multiple exits?? I still haven't tried the second way that I saw on youtube video, unless it's changed that you have to play birthday room?
We waited for long for the new level so we're super excited that level 5 is out and we'll try it soon! While waiting we got the labyrinthine and escape the backrooms. They were somewhat different, but I think we all enjoyed this game the most in terms of the map size (not too much tedious walking or trying to find the right path), puzzle types and solvability, monsters and how to dodge them, we enjoyed this a lot! Also, we don't feel dizzy after playing for many hours straight, since it's a really big bummer for some games. Please lemme know if you have any questions concerns! :))

I absolutely love this game, possibly the best backrooms game ever released. The entities and overall eeriness really keeps you on edge and gives you a lot of thrill.

I started the game and already was too scared to play alone. So a friend joined and together it was hella fun! I love the combination of puzzle and horror and the feeling of being lost with the beginning of each new level. To find out what kind of monsters might be there and how they react on movement, sound or brightness, etc. was thrilling.

In contrast to what some other people said I did really enjoy the sewer level. It was way more relaxed than the ones before, so that one had enough time to search for items and figure out how the puzzles work. 

Even though, I have to admit, that we restarted the game in easy mode very early. We just didn't want to be game over when being close to the end of a level. But I guess for gamers seeking a challenge, the normal or hard mode might be interesting.

The hotel level was my favorite so far! Please give us more of that! Loved the puzzles and the enemies were fun. Got caught by some pretty good jump scares. I liked that one was exploring different puzzles at the same time, so that there was always something to do and something to find out without the game feeling streamlined.

The only part that I found really annoying was the birthday party. If I'd have played alone that would have been the part where I'd have stopped playing the game. But with two people it is absolutely doable, just takes some time.

This is a super fun game. The puzzles are challenging and the game play is immersive.  If you're a horror fan this game will not disappoint. Just make sure you are ready for jump scares. 10/10 definitely worth the money!

You have a limited amount of lives using a respawn system. It uses steam co-op system for a total of THREE players, with proximity chat.

The enemies are not scary, they are extremely annoying and don't add a challenge to the game, just a block of pixels that continuously stay in one spot and never move and can kill you basically instantly. The puzzles are also awful, they are not fun to solve and the rewards are terrible. I have never seen a game with such poor level transitions either, the level variety doesn't feel different. I requested a refund on this game to salvage the wasted couple of hours that my friends and I experienced.

I really wanted to like this game based on its premise, but there were a lot of things that kept me from enjoying the game as much as I could. 

- The way the mouse seems to lag and then suddenly 'snap' when moving around can be very jarring. I've tried adjusting settings, but it doesn't seem to really addressing the issue with that sudden 'snap.'
- The blur and lighting is really hard on the eyes. Even turning film-grain off and tweaking the settings available, the lighting really leaves a lot to be desired. Being unable to see the people you are playing with who are standing close just makes it frustrating to work with.
- I understand the desire for immersion to have the player just dropped into the game where they have to figure stuff out, but that immersion is ruined when you have to bumble around for 15 - 20 minutes trying to figure out what you need to do. A better tutorial would help this, or some better design. 
- It feels like the large bulk of the time is spent hiding in lockers, even with things like the screw driver to deter certain monsters. Having to deal with multiple entities who skulk about aggressively in the same spots (sometimes multiples at a time in an area) just kills the game's vibe for me.

There were some smaller issues that my group had when we played this game, but these seemed to be the biggest problems we all had. I would love to recommend this game, but I don't think I can until things such as these get some attention. The group I play with has played a variety of similar games (Dead by Daylight, Phasmophobia, Ghost Hunter Corp., Devour, Forewarned, etc) which all have their quirks, but the ones in this one seem a little more heavy-handed.

I wish the developers the best of luck, though! I can see a lot of potential in this game.

Saving system doesn't make any sense in this game. We got to the pool with some creatures swimming in office level, which required solving many puzzles and dealing with the skin-stealer, and escaping the b-day party stuff. The whole thing took a few hours to figure everything out and get to that point. However, the game didn't save any progress and next time we wanted to continue, we were back to the square one with everything needing to be redone. 

I don't understand what is the point of this strict saving or checkpoint system. I'm not sure it makes the game more challenging in a meaningful way and there's no point in doing all the puzzles and going through the same struggles. The level design of the game does not make it replayable anyway. Also, we play easy, at least at that level saving or checkpoints could be more generous.

All that happened above turned my initially positive experience into a negative one and don't plan on going back to the game and do all the same stuff all over again.

After playing this game I can say I enjoyed it and found it to be an overall good experience,
that being said a few things that could be done to make the game more immersive I will list the things in my opinion that could be done.

1. More immersive visuals, some of the game feels like it came out of a GMOD, and I only say that because the NPCs are very generic and so is the overall atmosphere of the levels, such as walls, furniture, bodies, entities, this is something that could be improved and would by far and would make the game so much more enjoyable

2. The mechanics, these for sure need to be improved, the walking, running, crouching, sprinting, and also their should be more options such as jumping and climbing, you could keep the challenge adding these options, simply make these much more physically demanding mechanics use more stamina, also the stamina should be set with he health, if you have low health why would you have normal stamina?
also swimming mechanics will definitely be a must because in backrooms lore, there is multiple backrooms levels with water, and that in itself is an endless possibilities of level;s and so and so forth, Poolrooms anyone?

3. This game is missing so much, I mean there are of course limits to everything, but this game has unlimited potential, some things that should be added is a more open world experience, now i know what your thinking, How the heck is the backrooms an open world experience? well you can No-Clip anywhere if you hit the wrong wall, this could expand into even more levels, and different possibilities, such as trading with other survivors, NPCs, and i mean an open world game, gets more players and is overall more enjoyable.

3. as i mentioned NPCs, this just needs to be improved overall, like i said the copy paste thing, it can take away from immersion really fast and make the game dull for some people, a game should grab the players attention and  make them feel like their actually being challenged and actually making hard decisions, but nothing breaks the immersion more than seeing the same face or same corpse or same NPC over and over and over again, and NPC,s should definitely be more lifelike, for example the entities, it seems like they just go back and forth and back and forth and have no real chasing or hunting mechanic.

but this is just friendly criticisms, and I really hope that this game take a good direction and really grows and thrives, I of course know its still being developed and will take time to create, and build, and grow, but this has endless possibilities, and I really hope to see them come to light.

The game has potential, but is currently not very fun to play.

Some things that are holding the game back are:

- The level design is very repetitive, they're all pretty much just fetch quests with a couple easy puzzles.

- The enemy difficulty does not change with game difficulty.

- The game has multiple game-breaking bugs, one of which has existed since last year.

- The VR mode's controls suck.

- You need to beat certain levels to unlock some skins and cosmetics, which doesn't make a lot of sense given that there are only a couple of levels and they don't have much replay value at the moment.

- Overall the game is kinda boring because of the repetitive level design and lack of levels

I really want to love this game, but the developers make it very hard.

Perhaps not strictly true to the 'endless' nature of the Backrooms, since it heavily relies on puzzle solving as a condition for progression, whereas the original nature of the Backrooms is endless exploration and desolation, but it's still good fun! Everything you pick up during the game has a use. It makes sure to include each nook and cranny of the level design in order for you to obtain every item that you will need for progression.

There are three difficulties with a variety of scaling when it comes to health, stamina, lives, revive time, etc. Easy is definitely the best difficulty to play on if you're after a more casual experience I would say, as there are less drawbacks compared to playing on Normal and Hard. On top of that, as you unlock new levels, you can choose to spawn from those levels going forward, which is very nice, as I wouldn't enjoy having to replay the entirety of the game if I wanted to simply spawn at my desired level.

The very first level is monster-free, you can explore safely but the non-saturated colours and the sound of the level is very off putting. I think they did a very good job in capturing the uneasiness of the Backrooms with the first level, even if it's very short and brief - as with any good horror game, there's a sense of dread and uncertainty. Definitely a strong sense of eerieness as you'd expect from the Backrooms.

The second level is a variation of the first and is darker, known as the Dark Rooms. As you explore, you will find various other levels such as the Parking Lot and the Office as well as secret levels such as Level Fun, Level ! (Run for your life!), and the Sewers, with a new level coming later this month which my friends and I are incredibly excited for.

There are multiple endings to the game which provides you with a lot more play time. My friends and I thoroughly enjoyed this game. There was initial tilt when we played the Sewers for the first time, but I think it really got us to co-ordinate and get our brains working, and overall, I don't regret any of the play time on this game. We replay the game and we have some very good laughs, and enjoy replaying through some of the levels.

I absolutely recommend playing this game if you enjoy survival horror games, as well as puzzle solving. Especially with a group of friends, I would say this is a 'must-play'.

If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

6 tablespoons unsalted butter

1/2 cup white sugar

1/2 cup brown sugar

1/4 cup water

1/4 teaspoon cinnamon

1 pinch salt

5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced

1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).

Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.

Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.

Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.

Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.

Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

I ask you, dear reader, what would you do with 15 hours? Well, you could learn the basics of Quantum Physics, or maybe study for whatever is coming up in school. For me, for poor, naive me, this 15 hours was spent on this piece of bullshit that shouldn't even exist. But it wasn't just the 15 hours that makes me mad. It was the fact that during the days I could not stop thinking about this game. During the nights I would constantly dream of the dimly lit hallways of the Darkrooms. The hours I spent strategizing and theory-crafting, the rage that I spewed out at the friends I played this with. This game turns you into a toxic monster who's only goal is to escape the backrooms. 

This game is not unlike a parasite. You download it, play it once, and forget about it. But the desktop shortcut left on your PC will slowly become ingrained in every aspect of your life. Your next days will leave you yearning for more, and resistance is futile. You *will* click on that icon again. You *will* succumb to the urges to travel those liminal hallways once again. Perhaps your new obsession will carry over to your friends, who will suffer a similar fate to you. 

You and your friends will finally find the way out of the backrooms after countless attempts through sleepless nights. And then you may ask yourself: "That's all, right?" No. That most certainly is not all. Every death and hardship followed by success makes you a slave to the grind. You will return for more. To complete the game from Floor 0. To complete the game deathless. To complete the game in under 35 minutes. And you will continue the arduous work until you finally achieve everything that this game could possibly offer.

Then, and only then, are you done. But like a cancer, this game never truly goes away. Not left in check, the urges will fester and the need for a fix will slowly creep back into your system. And then you will continue your servitude to the backrooms, its entities, and the endless halls that captured your mind when you first clicked "Play" all those months ago.

Unfortunately, Inside the Backrooms doesn't carry out the magic of the popular creepypasta. Although the game tries to bring horror elements together with gloomy atmosphere, dark rooms, and the creatures you can see in every backrooms game, it just doesn't work out and the game falls short of "horror". The game provides too little in terms of gameplay to keep you afraid of anything since you are thrown into an arena of creatures right at the beginning of the game. Thus, this leaves almost nothing for you to experience as you progress. 
Also the stamina system in this game is designed to deliberately slow the player down. Due to the fact that you get heavily punished for using your stamina (and worse if you fully deplete it), you are forced to spend a lot more time than you should in this game. 
Inside the Backrooms needs more than what it provides to be a satisfactory experience.

Backrooms be lacking in its narrative and character development. The game does not offer much in the way of backstory or lore, which can make it harder for players to become invested in the world or its inhabitants.

Ultimately, while Inside the Backrooms may appeal to fans of horror games or internet urban legends, it may not offer enough variety or depth to keep players engaged for long periods.

[h1]Tl;dr : The game has great ideas and puzzles but the stamina system makes it unbearable and a good portion of your time with the game will be waiting for your staminia to regain itself or dying because of it.[/h1]

The game has genuine potential and does require some significant brain usage when it comes down to the puzzles rather than "Pull 3 levers to open the door" type puzzles.
I especially liked the safe code puzzle and computer dycryption puzzle.
The vibe is great, i felt uneasy and fear at the start and it does atmosphere quite well alongside some monsters i didn't see before being introduced ( like the pool monster ).
I like the ideas and challenges presented here and were certainly the fun, interesting parts i had with this game...

[b]HOWEVER[/b], the problem that keeps me from recomending it and ruins its pace, is that a good majority of the time you'll be running away from monsters but the stamina system ( EVEN IN EASY DIFFICULTY ) is [i]HORRIBLE[/i] with the stamina regeneration feeling like it takes [i]20-25 seconds[/i] if not more to replenish fully and get used up in a matter of [i]7 seconds[/i] with higher difficulty increasing stamina consumption and monster damage which i don't even know how you'd be able to tolerate unless you like getting your balls kicked in repeatedly.

The best example of this is in the birthday level of this game, [u]you got a time limit and literally have to run to do your tasks before the timer runs out and get insta killed by the monster[/u] , but with such a [i]GARBAGE[/i] stamina duration and regeneration, unless you get really lucky [i]( which is never a good thing when developing any game )[/i] you'll get hunted down by the active monster or outright insta killed on the spot, you can't sneak this or hide, you have to be quick which this game really does a good job of making it as [b]tedious and painful[/b] as possible.

Yes, there's some levels where you can [i]"sneak"[/i] around the monsters and in the later levels are encouraged to do so such as the "Party level" but that level you literally have 3+ monsters that can instantly kill you, your hiding spots aren't exactly "safe" ( no lockers either ) and worst of all, they give you a 10 second break period where the monsters are temporarily disabled and then enabled them again for 30 seconds and vise versa, and during all that you have to [u]collect 5 body parts with varying quantities.[/u]

They're basically encouraging you to sneak and hide but if you get spotted you're screwed anyways because you can't run for more than 5 feet before needing to regain your breath like a fat man climbing up the [b]STAIRS[/b].
And even if the monster doesn't instantly kill you before, you're unable to do ANYTHING and will die regardless before you can run again, which can make some puzzles fustrating and chases just a death wish and unpleasant.

Outside of that, it's worth mentioning that the game runs alright with some lag spikes here and there with some visible visual and gameplay bugs at times, and some puzzles having awkward handling ( like the safe code puzzle ) but this is a 5$ game, i went in with that expectation in mind.

Note : I finished the game and played it entirely in multiplayer with 2 friends getting all endings.

To be fair, the game does have its flaws. There were never any clear signs or instructions for the players to follow when it comes to solving their puzzles. There was also no information given about what the collect items do. It does make the puzzles more interesting since you have to find out the hard way, but in this case the game just felt more tedious because of it. I didn't even know what moth jelly does until defeating my first ending. Furthermore, this plays negatively when combined with their incredibly large maps that are so easy to get lost in. There is no mini map either and honestly the game was a lot more fun after finding a map online just to beat the sewers level. If they had a more instructional HUD given to the players, I think this will elevate the already outstanding performance of this game.It has an incredible ambiance of dread and fear, I was never certain if the smiley entity will just backstab me again because I was in the dark. I was terrified of the very first level and, honestly, that first level was a really great experience. So great that I ended up playing because I saw my friend's gameplay when they tried to defeat level one. It is personally my favorite level because of the variety of entities/monsters, its intriguing puzzles, and a very immersive environment. The game was also pretty challenging making it a more extended gameplay and worthwhile experience once the player beats the game. It is also not too challenging and it feels beatable and possible without online aid. Even if you use online sources as an aid, it ends up performing as a manual DIY HUD system for the player which basically counters the main weakness of the game and turns it into a more socialized experience (although, I still think they should have added a HUD system alongside a mini map). Overall, I highly recommend this game to be played with friends and family. It gives very good scares, a lot of teamwork, and a very interesting, and rewarding experience for its players. Additionally, the game is, unfortunately, significantly harder when performed alone or by pair so I recommend a team of at least 3 or 4 people. I already achieved all endings and I am STILL planning to play the fist level again or to beat the game a second time but this time with the rest of my friends (if I could convince them to play horror haha).
