Currently one of the best coop Backroom games and has a fair bit of content. An average run takes between 2-3hrs to complete, and the game has multiple endings. The puzzles are neat and varied and the entities all have different behavior and strategies to avoid. The game's still unfinished but it's worth the current price. I didn't try the VR mode but it runs pretty great on my mid to high end machine.

The few gripes I have with the game right now would be:
1) Some entities can clip through terrain/walls and attack you.
2) Places where multiple entities can attack you will have them corner you in almost guaranteed death situations. [spoiler]Cable/Bacteria entity chasing you in a room while the Smiler blocks the exit.[/spoiler]
3) Certain puzzles are difficult to read if players are nearby as their flashlight or shadow will blind you. Would be nice to have those blocked out while doing those puzzles as the game already puts you into a unique puzzle mode while doing them.
4) A level later on has a mechanic that was either broken when I was on it and made it seem unfair or it's just set to being too hard IMO. [spoiler]The pool area with the arms creatures lurking inside. For me their model wasn't visible and they made no noise or ripples in the water. The only way to detect them was with a motion detector found earlier on, but even with that the pings for location tracking were too sparse. By the time I'd get info on locations they'd have already gotten me. Lost my first run on normal difficulty by losing my seven remaining lives in just this area. Since they move it proves very difficult to just go slow and safe. Only reason I think this area was bugged for me was that another level has the same entities but they can be seen and heard in the water.[/spoiler]
5) Skipping the opening cut-scene seems to kick players if you're the host. Had this happen several times so I just stopped skipping them to help avoid this problem.
6) Later levels give you a lot of recovery items but most of the entities are one shot kills to you, mostly defeating the purpose of the healing ones. This is more of a gripe about the balance between multi-hit kills and one-shot kills as the earlier levels had a lot more multi-hit kill entities which gave you a chance to heal.
7) A certain entity has a long range one-shot kill attack that I never truly figured out. I'd just hide for longer than I needed to to make them go away as I couldn't deal with them otherwise. [spoiler]The Smiler entity has a very odd way of killing you from a distance. Initially I thought you just needed to not stare at them as you'd lose sanity, and to not touch them as they would one-shot kill you. However apparently if they see you for long enough they'll kill you even from long distances. Breaking line-of-sight works but I guess it's a certain amount of time they need to spot you for them to get that long range kill. What's more is that the attack is either on a timer or the cool-down after breaking LOS doesn't reset, so if you get seen and hide but decide to peek several seconds later to see if they're gone, they can kill you almost instantly.[/spoiler]
8) Certain parts of the game has huge frame drops, including when using certain items [spoiler]The flesh in the sewer[/spoiler]. It's disorienting and when it does happen it's normally when I'm trying to avoid an entity. My camera will jitter and I'll need to reset myself quickly to not die.
9) Even though the puzzles have plenty of hints, I've found that most people give up and disconnect on just the first level. There's multiple puzzles going on at once and it seems to overwhelm or confuse them and they either silently give up and follow me around or leave. Only managed to do a fully play-through with my brother as everyone else left before finishing the first level.
10) A in-game notebook would be handy. I've played some Backrooms games with this feature for jotting down notes or creating maps as you play. This would be really handy as there's several puzzles that involve memorization. What I ended up doing is either taking screenshots of clues I find or using an external notepad app but it'd be nice to have it built-in.

Even with these current issues I still think the game is worth getting in its current state and price. If the dev continues to add more content and fix the wonky parts of the game it'd make it even better.

This game is charming and a great experience to play with friends! There's some weird bugs and a few really awful moments you have to drag through, but overall I've had fun!

Biggest bug I ran into: In an online game, one of us died in the sewers to a rat. When he respawned, a rat was on top of his body and began to push him. Due to the way the rats work, he couldn't move. The rat pushed him out of the world boundary and he fell, and with no way to reset himself we had to completely restart the level.

Worst part of the experience: [spoiler]The hallway chase when getting the ending required for the Lost Inside the Backrooms achievement. This chase was clearly only programmed assuming the player both had and consumed a Moth Jelly, but when my group arrived to it none of us did.[/spoiler] Cue a slow, six minute chase where we would die, respawn, walk ten feet or sprint as far as we could, get killed, revive, repeat. Either giving the player a Moth Jelly right outside the chase to ensure they use it or giving the players a better sprint in this chase is a must, because not every player will continuously hoard an item they can only hold two of in a game where running from monsters is a 24/7 game (ESPECIALLY online, where players will aggro monsters just to buy their friends time on puzzles.)

These are just two small-ish parts of a bigger experience though. I really have enjoyed this game! If you have a group of friends, this game is a great and inexpensive experience where you'll definitely get some laughs.

Overall pretty good game until the last level, however I have some points;

It's a very fun co-op experience (I played it with my little brother) until the last level, the sewers. Up until that point it's decently challenging, requires a bit of puzzle solving skills, requires cooperation skills, is a little bit scary and not too repetitive. Then when you reach the final level it gets rather boring. It took me and my brother ca 2,5 hours to finish the last level and after like 1,5 hours we got tired of it. There's no way to save so you can't really take a break to finish it later which only made it even duller and you felt forced to complete it. The puzzles get repetitive and you're really slow which leads to you progressing very slowly.

It's really not a good backrooms game either. There's too much things going on at the same time which kind of takes you out of the eerie liminal space feeling that the backrooms is trying to bring out. The whole reason backrooms is scary is because you don't know what's lurking in the hallways, you don't know whether you're alone or not, you don't know anything about this place and it's too empty. This game is quite the opposite, it's easy to figure out where the entities are which removes that feeling of not knowing what's lurking and there's too much happening which removes the eerie horror feeling of the backrooms and you get to know the areas pretty quickly. It's a pretty fun puzzle game but not a good backrooms game.

This is of course 100% my opinions and you may like this game. You may not even read all this lol.

For a $5 game, it's worth but there are Pros and Cons (as to be expected). Gameplay was fun due to the puzzles not being too complex that would normally make it annoying to play. Though, there are a two things (that I can remember) that bothers me when playing the game, mechanic-wise. And yes, I know that it's still in Early Access (as of writing this) so bugs/issues are to be expected. Plus I understand there are bound to be bugs/issues.
(May Mention Spoiler(s))

First off is the lack of motion blur settings. When I was playing this game with my friend(s), the biggest issue is the constant blur happening on the screen, making it nauseating to play. I understand it's part of a game mechanic but there should be another method of showing that you have "anxiety". My friends and I mainly struggled playing the game because of this.

(Mentions Spoilers)
Second is some of the AI. In the sewers, Entity#25 tends to get bunched up together with its friends at a specific wall because of their mechanic requiring hearing. It's due to a certain puzzle causing a lot of noise that even when it is stopped, they most likely stay at that wall. Then there's the Entity#10 in the third section. Would've been nice if it actually copied someone's look to make it more terrifying as it is in it's name. Its description mentions that it can smell blood over long distances basically meaning (from my guess) it will know where you are and hunt you down if you're not full HP. That mechanic does not entirely work because it more rather reacts to the usage of anxiety pills or seeing a player. Last one I want to mention is Entity#3. Just the fact that there's a room leading to the radiation suits that room is entirely dark, meaning it will show up a lot or it has a high chance of showing up making it frustrating to play around that point.

(Mention Spoilers)
In conclusion, mentioning these does not mean the game is unplayable, just more troubling to play. Regardless, I did enjoy playing the game love how my friends and I played our own part when playing this game. The game immediately drops you into the horror with at least some instruction(s) on what you're up against or what you're doing. The scariest monster to me would be Entity#67 while the best section to me is the first part (when the entities are able to hunt you). Entity#67 to me is just horrifying because of how narrow its second "game" is. Just the risk of having to make turns in a narrow maze to potentially see that thing is very terrifying. So terrifying, I was too afraid to leave the corner panicking while my friends were searching for the boxes. While that may be scariest monster to me, the section I like the most is the first one (as fore-mentioned when the entities are able to hunt you) because the maze that is given is not too complex for me to memorize but also not too easily memorized as well (apparently to my friends). For a $5 game, I recommend this game. it's really worth giving it a try.

The VR Feature practically doesn't work, I don't get Motion Sickness a lot but this game really made me feel like it. The whole time I could see my player models head, and had to turn my camera away from items to even pick them up, also you can't read notes. Now playing it outside VR, it still wasn't good, better but not good, wall textures were clipping, which is fine but kinda easy to resolve, also you can't even see the player model in normal play so why can you see it in VR, no idea. An entire wall was missing, I can't tell if it was missing or a horrible mirror, as when you see the wall it has an invisible wall blocking you from falling in, the edges of it were black so probably not missing, and if it was a mirror pretty crappy job cause it didn't reflect what was supposed to reflected and instead showed a image of the backrooms, low res so you could count the pixels not game breaking but horrible nevertheless. Also for the record I'm a scaredy cat, I get scared by the babiest of things but this game was not scary, not even in VR, it might have been but it's kinda hard to see when there's a giant face in the way, I literally ran in to Smiler and felt nothing, could have been the jumpscare but whatever, ran into another Entity, the one that's a stickman, and again felt nothing. Oh and you don't die first hit, why??? NO IDEA. that's the least scariest thing, imagine playing a game that's supposed to be scary and, seeing the monster, it gets you, it just sits there... waiting to hit you again. There is also a life system, at least in the multiplayer so take that as you will. Now I normally don't review or refund things even if they're bad, as I don't want to be rude but this game had it comin, and it's fairly certain that the game was made to go with the trend which is fine, if you do it well, the intro cutscene has a Gmod Nextbot, and clearly the VR was a rush job so they can slap it on the games page, and I heard one of the game creators said to not buy the game for the VR, and you shouldn't do that, well then don't have it as a VR Supported Game. TL:DR VR Sucks, Games weird, Creators rude. just play Escape the Backrooms instead.

[b]Among the many terrible $5 Steam horror games, this is [u]NOT[/u] one of them![/b]
This game will give you and your friends around 3-4 hours of puzzles, mazes, and [i]lots[/i] of chases.

[hr][/hr]

Critiques:
[list]
[*]Puzzles are enjoyable and fun but controls for interacting with the puzzles can be very clunky.

[*]The animations could use some polishing.

[*]There 100% needs to be some form of a hotbar/item wheel to quickly swap between different items in your inventory.

[*]In my opinion, the horror aspect should be kicked up a few notches. The monsters and environment are not scary enough visually/audibly.

[*]Once you learn the monster's patterns and behaviors, a lot of the challenge is removed and the thrill drops significantly. I don't want to feel like I can puppet them around in the palm of my hand. I want to feel nearly hopeless and be holding my breath till the finish line.
[/list]

[hr][/hr]

Overall, the game is [b]easily[/b] worth the price and I am eager for future updates.

For a game about being trapped in a seemingly infinite and ever-changing liminal space, the game is extremely linear. You're not actually in the backrooms proper for most of the game, and when you are, the lack of looping paths and corridors not attached to dead-end setpieces make the whole area feel like one small, enclosed, elaborate puzzle rather than a real place. I want to get lost. I want to feel like I've seen the same place over and over because being unable to ground yourself geographically in what should feel like an impossible space is part of the fun. 

Everything past the first area is either a straight line or at best a T-junction. This means that monsters, if around, will pretty much never despawn or leave you alone. They're also nearly impossible to get rid of for the same reasons. Combined with the mediocre spatial audio and the gameplay is much more frustrating than tense or scary.

Oh, and the VR experience is terrible. Interactive items are often unusable, making the game literally unplayble in VR. Not that you would want to, since the camera is placed in such a way that you're constantly clipping into your character's model. Do NOT buy this game if you're planning to play it in VR.

I am a 55 year old biker and trucker father, and probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 15 now. My son got this game for from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 12 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he let me borrow his controller. Me and my son then played in turns and I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my son many happy memories.

For 5 bucks it's well worth it. here are my recommendations to fully enjoy it:

-Jump in blindly, don't go and spoil yourself because that'll ruin the fun.
-Play with friends.
-Use the in-game proximity chat.
-Go for the achievements.

I haven't been playing for long, but the horror aspect has already left. The puzzles seem interesting but is bogged down by the constant bombardment of the 'entities' that happen with such frequency that they just aren't scary, but tedious. 

When you die, you are granted invincibility and encouraged to go explore rooms you haven't seen yet, leading to situations where I am running into new things while invisible, making the game even less scary. 

the tldr for me is, good puzzles, tedious monsters. The game tells you to 'stare at the hound to survive it'. Seems the hound isn't worried about this suggestion. 

I'm hoping playing on easy makes it a bit more fun. But i'm supposed to be scared, not frustrated.

Good quality for the price, fun with friends! Scary, anxiety inducing, sweaty palms game.
Multiple levels, puzzles not too hard but still challenging. You can progress before completing all puzzles in some areas, but game will provide missing key items when loading next level [spoiler]accidentally bypassed finding hammer/smashing vases/finding fuses etc on first run and game continued smoothly.[/spoiler]
I believe there could be multiple endings? As my group escaped without touching the sewer. Will definitely play again to experience the sewer!

Some glitches are to be expected, and I have experienced host crashing just once in 9 hours of gameplay. No glitch has required restart so far.

Some of the notes/entity information sheets feature broken English, but are easy enough to understand. The only entity which seems not to follow the rules as listed on its sheet is [spoiler]the dog. Information states that he is intimidated by eye contact/staring but he just keeps attacking us - just need to lose him. Potentially the sheet is written wrong and you need to avoid eye contact?[/spoiler]

For an early access indie game, the dev is surprisingly active with updates, and I'm confident that they will improve this game with time!

I am a 55 year old biker and trucker father, and probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 15 now. My son got this game for from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 12 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he let me borrow his controller. Me and my son then played in turns and I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my son many happy memories.

You can also unlock 2 outfits, one by getting the Flesh Cake ending and one by getting the Sewer Ending (which is extremely long and boring), however these outfits are purely cosmetic and do not grant any sort of "special" power making them unappealing to unlock, maybe one could give you unlimited stamina, while the other unlimited health, just to give the player a reason to fully explore this game.

I think this game has a lot of potential and could be really fun, but the party room ruins EVERYTHING. Firstly, the timer is too short, and the monster in the maze with the walls 1 hit kills you. With the scaling to find the presents in the maze, it uses most of your lives to get through the maze. If you make it out of the maze with the physical walls, then you get to the TAPE MAZE. The same monster is in that maze, but this time, the monster can run through the walls, immediately to you. If one player solves the maze, gets the keycard objective of the room, and leaves, the monster still hunts down the other players who hadn't made it out of the maze yet. I lost all of my lives in the maze and had to spectate my friends finishing the game. I think this game could be great if they gave you a bit more leniency with the party room level, and give you the option to turn off the maximum 10 lives per player. As of right now, I would not recommend this game.

I have played this game a lot and I think it is, interesting to say the least, but a few warnings, this game can be infuriating. For one, almost all the entities camp the objectives for example, the hound camps a vase room you need to be in for a while, I tested it a while ago (though this isn't true now) and when you break the first vase (if not there already) the hound comes in through the vent. The hound also camps the lever room which also has smilers (which have their own problem) which makes the lever room a "hope the hound and or smilers don't show up" game which isn't fun nor is it scary, although I haven't noticed the camping as much though I've probably gotten better at avoiding the camping. The bacteria camps either the room to the left of the mirror and only moves when you approach it or leave the area, or a tight hallway leading to an important room and never leaves the hallway. Second off, the smilers are the worst thing in the game hands down. The smilers' whole "gimmick" is spawning in hallways leading to important areas, or in large open spaces and if you look at them for more than 2 seconds, you die instantly. All this does is slow down the game and makes the player bored. Sometimes smilers even spawn on you killing you instantly, they kill you when you aren't looking at them, or they spawn around a corner you can't see. Smilers are bad additions to the game that should be removed or revamped. Maybe this review will be outdated but at the time I'm writing this, it isn't really. I will give it to them though, past the darkrooms is pretty solid and the darkrooms are fun to learn for the first time, the parking garage can be annoying but you can dodge the skin-stealer pretty easily, the office rooms has a skin-stealer with a repeating walk cycle and doesn't really camp at all, not to mention, the fun games are pretty fun. The pools are easy, and the sewers are pretty fun to learn but I can see how sewers can be annoying. Thanks for listening to my Ted-Talk.

Inside the backrooms... This game is super fun with friends, nothing too difficult or complex. Got some good levels with some fun monsters to avoid who will probably give you a good couple scares, until you get to the sewers. Why games feel the need to add a sewer level to every game is beyond me. 

The level is simply not scary, not fun, and extremely poorly designed. Sprawling tunnels that are too difficult to map in your mind and would take you hours on the level to remember, (you will want to spend the least amount of time as possible on this garbage section). All items and places you need to get to are on complete opposite ends of the level. The water is annoying, makes you go even slower through the boring level, the concept would be fun in small uses and sections but in this you cannot avoid having to walk through it. The rats are the least threatening enemy in the game, not scary just fucking irritating. Just stop moving and you're good. There is nothing tense, scary or fun about them and it again makes the level sooo slow. The rats also can glitch through the railings slightly, so when they're walking down the sewer and you're on the side of it (where you should be safe), they still get you. I don't know why im wasting time on this review. Good game up to the sewers. Its the worst and I hope they adjust it, it should get destroyed. It smells, it looks the same everywhere you walk, I hate it, my friends hate it, my dentist would not recommend it. I am a 55 year old biker and trucker father, and probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 15 now. My son got this game for from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 12 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he let me borrow his controller. Me and my son then played in turns and I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my son many happy memories.

This game is very good, and fun :))    
How long it took to complete the main game: around 2 hours and 30 minutes
how long it took to complete sewer level: 3 hours and 33 minutes  ( we were confused for the first hour )
How long it took to complete Run for your life: around 11  minutes  ( mainly retries )

This game may not be as fun for other people who aren't as good at puzzles, or want to take breaks after a level or 2. This wasn't as fun for one of my friends because you had to complete it in one go.  I recommend a tutorial  if you want to try to get the game done faster, and not spend so much time on one thing. 

levels/ puzzles/ entities : The levels were great, My personally favorite was Level 0.  My least favorite was the sewer because some of the puzzles were confusing and it took a long time.   Th entity for the next 2 levels was annoying, but we managed to get through.  Sometimes it would camp the lockers, which made it harder for us to complete the computer code. Partygoer ( minigame part not the level  )  was tiring because of the maze part where we had to find the presents. There was nothing else to really comment on. 

The only thing I found that I personally didn't like was the fact sometimes when you have to find the door when you're dead it can take quite a while because of how big a map is. This only applies for level 0,  since all the other levels were smaller or didn't randomized where the door was.  There is also a bug for VR where I get stuck outside of the elevator when i go in it. That may be just me, but I wanted to report it anyway just in case. 

 Overall,  I rate this game a  8.7/10 
Levels: 9/10
puzzles: 7.5/10 
entities: 9/10 
Entertainment: 9.5/10

The game is good and fast paced at the beginning but has a quick drop off in quality as you go further in. The sewer area for example is far too slow and is extremely boring and tedious to get through as there is no excitement. There as issues such as spawning back in just to die to a monster sitting on your body and the monsters glitching and killing you when you are no where near them. The sprinting mechanic is also very sloppy as the walking speed is painfully slow and the loud breathing is extremely annoying when you run out of stamina. This game is alright but i hope it becomes better on complete release.

The game is fun. The levels never change and for a game built on puzzles it is nearly impossible to win with a screaming Mexican child flipping switches and taking the key items. Communication is detrimental for every single run yet next to no one knows how to use the chat or voice chat. Tutorial also doesn't exist.

Edit: Came back after another 4 hours for a total of 6 hours. The game is early access but still has a huge potential for a great game. Found a group i was able to play with and had an amazing time despite bugs.
Known Bugs:
Rats in the sewers commonly no clip through the fence causing an insta death
Multiple entities can (and will) camp your body ASAP (insta death from respawn)
Many instances of entities making no noise (Also instadeath)
Hitboxes on gnomes (seasonal event) is very janky
Moving your screen too fast results in the screen splitting into 2 for a brief moment
Flashlights cause insane light pollution if used too close to a surface
Oil line un-interactable making the sewers unplayable (Wasted an hour I hate this game)

Please keep in mind this game is in early access from a very small team, what they have made is an awesome concept with mediocre execution. Even with these bugs,  7/10

I am a 55 year old biker and trucker father, and probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 15 now. My son got this game for from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 12 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he let me borrow his controller. Me and my son then played in turns and I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my son many happy memories.

It's a good game! Don't get me wrong. I played it with my boyfriend, but it took forever to complete. It was scary at first, and really fun, but by the time we got to a certain point with certain entities it went from fun and scary to annoying. We kept dying, and it got to the point where the entities were too hard to surpass, and we had to keep starting from the start of the level to get to where we were. Some levels should be separated. Having the entire game put into 2 levels was insanely unfair, and was annoying when we kept dying and having to start from the beginning of the level we were on. This was the worst with the 2nd level. We'd die, because the middle and final enemies were too hard, and then have to start all over with the puzzles, which made the game stale. It got much less scary, and the only real fear was fear that we'd die and waste all of our lives and have to start over.

Edit: After the sewer level came out my partner I essentially lost all our progress on the office level, and were expected to redo it in order to play the sewer level. Why can't we just play any level we want? Why does it have to go in order? It's not a story driven game. There is literally no story. There are no established characters, nothing. There is zero point to make people grind for hours to get the level done, especially if they just want to play it with their friends.

ALSO, the Devs in the community replies came off as major jerks. "Keep in mind a large majority of the players didn't have trouble playing the game, so rethink your strategy" in reply to someone complaining about how unfair and difficult the entities are. Seriously? It's true. The entities are incredibly OP and strong, and usually spawncamp. Not to mention the lag since the sewer update has been atrocious.

All in all I really like this game, especially the aesthetic and can't wait for more updates and fixes to make it even better

Okay so I like this game but don't like it at the same time. I love how there are challenging puzzles, great entities with some okay pathing, and just in all the environment is fantastic. One of my main problems is that the stamina is really low, this can affect a lot of things, such as in office room the "skin-walker" loves to chase and camp you so whenever you run out of stamina there really isn't anything you can do. Another complaint I have is that almond water is really no where to be found. I can find plenty of anxiety pills but there really aren't a lot of ways to heal. The next problem I have has to do with the party goer. The first 2 party games are find which are the popping balloons and the maze where you have to find presents, what I mainly hate about the third game is that it is extremely dark and the party goer doesn't go through the maze but instead goes over it and it really ruins the fun in that level and causes more rage due to it taking the majority of your lives if you don't get lucky. That really is all the problems I have run into so far, but besides that it is a great game and I do recommend it!

PS: I have tried the secret ending also known as the sewer level, and let me tell you running around for 3 hours trying to figure out things is unbelievable, thank god for tutorials. Seriously though what they need to do to the sewers is remove 50% of the entities and make the map smaller alongside this make the puzzles less complicated. There is no need for all that complexion! Over all though a good game! Highly recommend if you are into horror/puzzle games.

I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 2022 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

If you want a good few hours of fun playing a classic backrooms map then this game is for you and you can stop playing after the first level. However, if you want to play through the entire game. I cannot recommend this to anyone. The game starts fast paced you are running away from monsters and trying to survive while doing puzzles. Then it shifts with the second level as you mainly have to just hide in a locker from the monster while half completing puzzles. It doesn't seem like you need to really do the task on the computers in the second level? We never did that puzzle and decided to move on. 

However the party room on the second level was what I thought the worst level in game design. The first few puzzles start out pretty fun, pop the balloons, find the boxes. But MY GOD the candle mini game is absolutist terrible. The mini game has two big issues that could be solved. Either ONE give the play more stamina. Half the monsters you cannot outrun anyways in the game so having a terrible stamina system where you run 5 feet before coming to a crawling pace is just awful. OR give the players better flashlights. Its hard enough to see which direction the little red lines go. But when my flashlight cant show whats below me feet how am I supposed to find my way around in the 10 seconds you give me before the monster aimlocks though the lines. Now I thought the worst was over once we beat the party room mini game but man was I wrong...

The sewer level is one of the worst designed levels in any game I have ever played. It took us about 2 hours of trying to memorize and figure out the layout in general. On top of all the theme of the level is about being quite. Which means you are crouch walking around most of the time and when the cost is clear since the stamina system is so bad you end up getting to run for maybe 5 seconds before having to walk again. The game has this jelly that makes it so you can have unlimited stamina, however they give it to you way to late in the level. Another huge fault of this level is there are WAY to many things to do. After reading all the notes it was hard to keep track of what goes where. Please add a system where you can pick up the notes and read them in your inventory. Just to be met with another bullshit puzzle that we needed more parts (A bucket???) to get through. The Backrooms is an urban legend and creepypasta describing an endless maze of randomly generated office rooms and other environments. It is characterized by the smell of moist carpet, walls with a monochromatic tone of yellow, and buzzing fluorescent lights. Internet users have expanded upon this concept by creating different "levels" of the Backrooms and "entities" which inhabit them.

The original version came from a two-paragraph 4chan comment on a post asking for "unsettling images", where an anonymous user invented a story based on one of the photos. The Backrooms drew comparisons to various other horror trends and media, including the photography of liminal spaces, the SCP Foundation collaborative fiction project, and the six-hour-long album series Everywhere at the End of Time.

Since its original creation, The Backrooms has been expanded into various other forms of media and Internet culture, including video games, collaborative fiction wikis, and YouTube videos.

The Backrooms originated from a thread posted on the /x/ board of 4chan on 12 May 2019, where an anonymous user asked for others to "post disquieting images that just feel 'off'." There, the first photo depicting the Backrooms was uploaded, presenting a slightly tilted image of a yellow-colored hallway. Another anonymous user commented on the photo with the first story about the Backrooms, claiming that one enters the Backrooms when they "noclip out of reality in the wrong areas", which is a video game-related term originating from Doom for when a player passes through a physical boundary that would otherwise block their way.[1][2]

After the 4chan post gained fame, several Internet users wrote horror stories relating to The Backrooms. Many memes were created and shared across social media, further popularizing the creepypasta.[2] Some have stated they had seen that image somewhere before; in the opinion of Manning Patston from Happy Mag, these comments were "existential, hollow, and terrified".[2] Patston commented on the use of the term "noclip", interpreting it as "glitches in which the walls of reality are torn down", such as the existence of doppelgängers.[2] Comparing the location to the level design of the Resident Evil franchise, Kaitlyn Kubrick of Somag News called the Backrooms "the terrifying creepypasta of cursed dreams".[3]

The location of the original Backrooms photo is unknown. Although a number of locations have been proposed, it is possible that the image is a procedurally generated digital composition.[4] The creepypasta has also been associated with the concept of kenopsia, first coined in The Dictionary of Obscure Sorrows: "the eerie, forlorn atmosphere of a place that's usually bustling with people but is now abandoned and quiet".[4][5]

The Backrooms' original concept has been expanded by Internet users, who have created different "levels" of the location. There are thousands of levels found within fan made Wikis of the Backrooms, featuring different photos and "safety classes" in a format influenced by the SCP wiki. One canon is that there are three distinct levels.[2] The levels specified in this canon include:

Level 0 - The Lobby: This is the level depicted in the original Backrooms photo, featuring all of the creepypasta's most well-known characteristics – moldy carpet, yellow walls, and buzzing fluorescent lights. One of the entities created by users for this level are "hounds", described as disfigured and manic humanoid beings. Another feature of this level is a "noclip zone", which can bring wanderers back to Earth's dimension, return them to the starting point of Level 0, or to another level with different hostile organisms.[2]
Level 1 - Habitable Zone: A level reached when one chooses not to enter a noclip zone and instead wanders around Level 0 for days.[2] It is darker than Level 0 and features a more industrial architecture, with mechanical-like sounds being heard through the place. The level appears to be a dark, dingy warehouse with low-lying fog and puddles of water which randomly appear. In contrast to Level 0, the fluorescent lights begin to flicker more frequently, occasionally shutting down completely – "This is when the beings come out".[2]
Level 2 - Pipe Dreams: The third level of the Backrooms, according to the three-level interpretation.[2] It is one of the darkest levels, containing more industrial-like architecture. This level appears as long service tunnels with pipes lining the walls. It is described as being reached when one simply wanders around Level 1 for a long enough period of time, and featuring a much higher temperature than other levels. "Survivors" of the Backrooms claim that the only way to escape the level is to remain calm, stating that "Only when the backrooms have become your home can you depart."[2]

The Backrooms soon became popular from writers and Internet users, most of which commented on its uncannyness. The creepypasta has also been cited as the origin and most-well known example of the liminal spaces Internet trend, which are photos that evoke "a sense of nostalgia, lostness, and uncertainty";[7] the '#liminalspaces' tag has amassed nearly 100 million views on the social media platform TikTok.[6] When a woman named Claire Scheulin found an abandoned mall below her Airbnb, Internet commentators compared her photos of the place to the original Backrooms image.[8][9]

The horror aspects of The Backrooms drew comparisons to the conspiracy theories of UFOs in Area 51, to filmmaker Stanley Kubrick's work The Shining, to the Minecraft urban legend of Herobrine, and to the 2019 film Us.[2] Its ambiguous rooms has also been noted as featuring similarities to horror stories of the SCP Foundation, especially SCP-3008 (a branch of IKEA that contains an infinite interior space within a pocket dimension), and to the vague buildings of Control (2019).[10] Dazed called the Backrooms an example of "internet folklore".[6]

In January 2022, a short horror film titled The Backrooms (Found Footage) was uploaded to the YouTube channel of then 16-year-old director Kane Parsons (Kane Pixels on YouTube). It is presented as a 1996 recording of a young cameraman who accidentally enters the location, running from entities and entering other levels.[11] The film employs both live-action footage and 3D Blender renderings, as well as other techniques to create effects such as camera shake and a VHS filter.[12] Categorized by some as "analog horror",[13] the short received acclaim: WPST contributor Erica Russell called it "the scariest video on the Internet",[14] while Dread Central's Mary Beth McAndrews compared it to the 2019 video game Control and "watched it 10 times".[15][16]

Some were surprised by what Parsons did with what he had: Jai Alexis of website PopHorror was surprised by the director's age,[17] while The Awesomer noted that Backrooms "shows how to create tension without a budget".[18] Boing Boing's Rob Beschizza hypothesized that the creepypasta will eventually "end up in a slick but dismal 2-hour Hollywood movie", likening this prediction to the Slender Man creepypasta and its 2018 film adaptation.[19] When describing a meme of the Backrooms, GameRant's Tanner Fox called the short "a paralyzing watch which packs quite a bit of terror into its short runtime."[20]

Parsons has since uploaded twelve other videos relating to the Backrooms in non-chronological order as of 31 August 2022: The Third Test, First Contact, Missing Persons, Informational Video, Autopsy Report, Motion Detected, Prototype, Pitfalls, Report, Presentation, Found Footage #2, and I Remember.[10][21] They revolve around the fictional Async Foundation finding and exploring the Backrooms in order to solve "all current and future storage and residential needs",[22] with Informational Video referring to the location as Project KV31.[23] There are also five unlisted Backrooms videos uploaded by Kane, one of which references the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake.[24]

A nice cheap horror title where you can play with your friends and have lots of fun! Graphics are good and there is a good sense of fear that makes it great. Some nice puzzles too. Like others said, the fun room is not very fun. My favourite monster is by far the bacteria (we nicknamed him cable guy) because it is so fun to be chased by him. Least favourite is smiley (nicknamed spongebob) cause hes not very fun. The other monsters are pretty good too, but the best area in the game is the first area right after you get off the first elevator. I have not done the sewers yet, but the other areas (parking garage and office) are fun but just not quite as clever as the first bit with puzzles. And you gotta deal with meat boy (don't know his name) and he just keeps coming. Solid game though, so far provides a good amount of fun if you're looking for some cheap thrills. 8/10 Edit: I completed the multiple endings now. They do add some extra content, and are pretty great. I still believe the dark rooms area is the best, but these at least add some replayability. Hopefully they add more in the future as I would love to have some more areas to explore. If you do decide to try to find all the endings (I believe there are 4 in total) it can be a little tricky to figure out how to find two of them. One of them you come across in the parking garage (leads you to the area, the sewers) so that one is pretty easy, and the other one you come across in the office rooms as well, and that is pretty obvious (escape ending). However, the other two are not quite as clear. One of them involves a little bit of back tracking after the office (if you go that same route) and uses the computer too (this is the lost in the backrooms ending). The other one is called the fun rooms, which requires you to go back into the party room after finishing the party games (flesh cake ending). Although the lost in the backrooms ending (there are technically two but one is sewerage) is a bit tricky to find, it is quite easy to do. Same with the fun rooms. I would say the most difficult ending is the sewerage, but that is just because it takes the longest to do. Still believe it is an 8/10 game, most fun with friends.

VR Play: Do not buy this game if you saw "available in VR" and want to play exclusively in this mode. It's frustrating and fairly buggy in its current state. While it technically works in VR, the implementation feels clunky and sometimes things just straight up don't work. I've died to a monster, found my door, and been unable to recover my items many times in VR mode where desktop is not an issue. There is a particular puzzle that requires you to read some names from the floor. When interacting with these objects, the VR camera jarringly pulls the your body and view down to the floor to read the labels. It's at a strange angle and could easily induce vertigo in sensitive individuals. It also regularly forgets comfort settings (smooth vs. snap turning, etc.) after death. I was unable to choose a character in the VR version and, sadly, was unable to scare my friends by creeping along with some of the spookier player models. I would only recommend VR mode to VR veterans and those with patience. 

Outside of VR mode, the game is fun and the puzzle solutions are randomized with each playthrough. The layout remains the same if that makes a difference to you. The monsters do a good job of breaking the group up and slowing down progression in an entertaining way. They're also visually well designed and you can get some genuine spooks in certain spots. It's a great buy for $5 if you're planning to play mainly with keyboard and mouse. Make sure you have a good group of friends to play with - the kind you'd take to an escape room. For the time being, I'd recommend turning off ambient occlusion. Huge performance impact for not much difference in visual quality.

Inside the Backrooms is a masochistic "infuriate yourself" simulator. It is a giant maze that you will get lost in constantly, have to backtrack at times, and you'll get killed by the monsters pretty frequently if you aren't careful. BUT! It is a really fun game to play with a friend or 2. My first playthrough with another friend took a little over 3 hours, which might seem short, but the game is really cheap and still in development. The game has a story (kind of, only make sense once you finish) and 3 alternate endings, which will add more playtime if you so choose to go for them. The game has puzzles, which increase in difficulty as you go through the levels. I suggest doing the story mode on easy as on normal you only have 10 lives. As a side note: Unless you are an achievement hunter don't go the sewers route (the blue door in the parking garage), it's fucking terrible and you will waste at least 4 hours getting a shitty 3 second cut scene that isn't finished.

In the 5 hours that I have played the game, I never had a crash, which is good because there isn't a save function. From the main menu there is a "start at" feature, but it does reset all progress you've made.

Also, the party room wasn't a party room at all...
Starts strong then fizzles out at the end.

When I first looked into " Inside the backrooms" I did not know what to expect, but after much game time spent I realized this is a really fun game to play with friends, not only does it stimulate us but also challenges our communication and trust in each other. From The Cart Titan chasing us down the halls ,  to anxiety inducing party games in the office , and nice swim with the rats in the sewer. Its got it all really if you ask me. The cosmetics have also gotten so good with a variety of characters , they have teenage girls, homeless people, plague doctors, even the police!  This game has 3 settings of difficulty to your liking easy-normal-hard. I strongly suggest if its your first run to go for a more casual experience in the easy mode, this allows for unlimited respawns at all times as appose to normal which starts you at 10 lives.  Mechanics are pretty straight forward and the levels are very interactive and exclusively different in their own ways. I had lots of fun running this game so much I played it for 22 hours and if they do an update best believe ill be back for my filling. The best part of this whole thing is that its only $5 , yessirrr ! Id say its worth it 100% (: So get it now and enjoy~

The concepts behind the game are good and I like much of it so far, but there are multiple quality of life issues. The most important and why you should wait to buy this game until it exits early-access is just how long it takes to get to the first save point. I was playing with my friends and three hours in I was exhausted, stressed, and just wanted to quit. We hadn't gotten to the save point yet but we were all so mentally tired we just gave it up. It was very discouraging and by the end I felt like crying. The game was fun at first but going 3 hours with no ability to save made it feel like torture. If it weren't for that I would not have refunded the game. 

Other QOL issues are more minor and I'm sure will get better as the game updates. One was no way to move all of the contents of a 'death' box back into your inventory quickly. Another was the lack of a setting to change the amount of respawns before permanent death. While the limited amount of respawns is a nice touch to make the game scarier, not all players find that fun. The limit to respawns is especially frustrating given the fact that there are some areas in the game where it is easy to be spawn-killed (dog followed us into radioactivity room, did not leave the entire 15 minutes we were there and resulted in 7 deaths between the three of us because we could not do anything without being attacked). Similarly I died in a long hallway with ENTITY #10 and it would not walk far enough away for me to revive without being killed again. This was not helped by the fact that upon waking up both directions (towards the monster and towards safety) looked identical. 

Respawn loot looking the same for every player (yellow box) is also frustrating because in the hurry to pick up your things before you get attacked, it is easy to accidentally take some of the contents of a friend's box if they died next to you. It is then very difficult to drop all of their stuff as you have to open the item interaction menu and then click the drop button for every single item to give them to your teammate, which is difficult to do if you are about to be spawn-killed again. 

Occasionally smilies will spawn on top of you and insta-kill you which is very frustrating. This didn't happen to me personally but it happened to my friends on four separate occasions. 

I understand some players like to be kept in the dark about the details of the game, but some of the puzzles seemed non-obvious (or at least it is easy to miss something) and having a hints system would be a nice touch, especially for normal and easy mode. 

When you are in your 'ghost' state you can hear the footsteps of monsters but not see them. Seeing them would give an advantage to teammates, so it makes sense that you cannot see them. But in that case you should not hear them either because the sound of footsteps sounds similar to the heartbeat sound (which could also be made to be more clear and easier to follow.)

Finally there need to be more audio settings for both the in-game comms and otherwise. My mic was extremely quiet for some reason in game and I was entirely inaudible for my teammates, so we had to join a discord call so they could hear me. This was unfortunate because it meant that we had proximity chat for them, but not for me (my teammates could hear me at all times). Although my team was audible, I have hearing issues and couldn't hear 50% of what they said in proximity chat. I wish there was a slider where I could turn my team up, but just turning down the game a lot helped. 

Overall the game has great concepts and I enjoyed it in the beginning, but I can't in good faith recommend that most people buy it until it has undergone more changes (mostly regarding the save system). That said, keep an eye on this game! If the developers do improve QOL, I think it will be a great co-op horror game that is easy for beginners but scary for all levels of gamers.

This game has a lot of potential for good scares at the start, but it quickly devolves into a frustrating and underwhelming experience. Item and monster spawns are somewhat random, which allows for some unique experiences, but it can also lead to a slog of back and forth fetch quests to complete puzzles. The many puzzles in the game are necessary to add some sort of challenge, but the types of puzzles don't feel like they fit well with the overall theme of the game. Sometimes an entity will just hang around your corpse after you die and when you revive it will immediately attack you; this is particularly frustrating for the entities that kill instantly. The worst section of the game involves running around a maze 3 times looking for 1, then 2, then 3 items, followed by running around another maze 5 times to interact with other items, each time with only about 15 seconds before an entity starts hunting you.

Since i finished this game to 100% i wanted to remake my review of this game so let me rate all of the levels. played most of this game coop with 1 friend and sometimes solo for achievements.
***There are 3 Difficulties: Easy  
                                      Normal
                                      Hard
We played All of the but we didn't finish the hard dificullty since its nearly impossible. for begginers i recommend easy and if you beat it once then try normal

***Backrooms (Level 0) - it is a decent level to start with, the elevator puzzle took me 30 min first time we played it. There are no threats in this level. 7/10


***Backrooms (Level 1) - in my opinion, this is the greatest level in the game and where we had most fun and were scared, puzzle's were fun and actually made us use our brains and felt rewarding. There are 3 threats: Smiley, Larry and The Hound. Smiley is the Simplest to avoid, if you see him, look away and run so he cant see you and you are good. Bacteria aka Larry will chase you if he sees you. you can tell if he is near you by the red lights near you, if you see red lights, run or hide in a locker. The Hound can be avoided by closing the vents with a screwdriver, but he is unavoidable in 2 sections, otherwise you can hide from him in a locker. i'd give this level 10/10 very fun


***Parking - is a very short but simple level. there is only 1 Threat: Skin-Stealer (we called him Deadpool for some reason) is a pretty simple but dangerous enemy, if he sees you, he will outrun you, you need to hide otherwise you are dead. i'd give this level 8/10 pretty spooky


***Office - oh god this level made us go insane, we streamed this game on youtube and i almost lost my mind since most of the puzzles were figured by me and it was too hard for me, i'm not saying it was badly designed, quite the opposite, it is perfectly designed and challenging, deffinitelly will make you use your brain the most... or walktrought but at least try to beat it without one, you will feel like a god. there are 3 Threats i believe, Skin-Stealer, the partygoer and the clump. the partygoer is very challenging the first time you play it, but if you play it many times, you will get used to it. i will not spoil it, its a pretty interesting section, the clump will not chase you but will kill you if you get near it, u need to use a motion tracker to know where it is, pretty interesting too. i'll mention it again, puzzle's are challenging but rewarding. i'd give this level a 9/10


***Right now there are 4 endings i believe and i will not spoil them all, but i'll say this, the newest one took us 10 hours to complete.

***Overall i'd give this game a 9/10 this is a very quality horror game and i'm really interested how it will develop further, it is only 4 euros it is definitely worth it solo or coop it doesn't matter. also this game is in vr too. i dont have a vr but i would like to get one and try this in vr. Definitelly a YES for me

I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single farther to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 2021 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So I decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

Playing this game I have experienced a roller coaster of emotions both good and bad

I love the Backrooms creepypasta, and this game manages to replicate very well what Backrooms would look like in real life. Every puzzle, every jumpscare and every tension moment the game gives you is just what I expected from the game. I played with a friend, the multiplayer and proximity chat are very immersive. I have to say that this game made me feel almost every emotion humanly possible in only a few hours of gameplay.

Sure, it still has room for improvement, in the stability, graphics, 3D models and stuff, but even the game being on Early Access, it is still a game worth buying, you will not regret it and will have lots of fun.

I'm thrilled to see what will be added and improved to the game on newer versions.

As of now I've sunked an ungodly 17.3 hrs into this game like a legend. Here's my thoughts.

This game is 110% worth playing IF YOU HAVE FRIENDS, I know it's a little too much to ask of you but hear me out. I am a lil scardey boi therefore I could not play this game solo, but with friends it made the purchase worth it and the experience GRAND. Every moment was pure comedic bliss and terror, my friends leading me towards false hope only for them to turn the corner and come face to face with the worst dog I've ever seen. We screamed, we laughed, we ran away in terror leaving each other behind to get eaten by tentacle man. 

Where my grievances arise:

Initial play through, the Party Room was HORRENDOUS with the amount of lives it ate away. It seemed so simple, a party right? Fun and enjoyable? WRONG! This balloon bastard takes evil to a whole new level, their only purpose being to kick your ass to kingdom come. HOWEVER, it is such a satisfying level when you can finesse it and escape. This level is for sure one to play without the lives turned on because you will be suffering a poor souls end trying to escape the backrooms with him leaving you a single life. Another grievance arises with the newest sewer level which is its own breed of evil, me and my friends were unable to escape the sewer (3 hrs) because of a bug that prevented the final door from opening. The level itself requires the player to use an online map of some kind because getting around there while avoiding the rats and knowing where to go is big hard. 

Overall, the game is a blast. I love me some indie horror that receives continuous updates AND EVENTS!!! That Halloween event was actually pretty cool even if it was just finding treats in the map to unlock skins, I enjoy collecting skins man it's my burden. Get this game if you got homies, and are down to sink in an ungodly amount of hours into completing a full 100% play through. Good luck. Have fun.

It's a shorter, yet well-crafted horror game that is best played with friends. The visuals create a very accurate atmosphere to the Backrooms aesthetic and can make for some very scary moments. The monsters are also very interesting with haunting animations and sounds that actually make you feel afraid as they approach you. Despite these qualities, I cannot recommend this game due to the fact that YOU CANNOT SAVE. As someone who doesn't always have an opportunity to play for long periods at a time, the option to save is detrimental. When my friend and I were getting decently far in the game and we decided to get off, the realization that none of our progress saved was devastating and completely depleted my interest in coming back to it. Unless you plan on dedicating the time to complete this in one session, I do not recommend this game until they add saving.
